animal.description:
Daisy May came to us, with her 11 puppies, from the southern tip of Texas from our partner shelter, Palm Valley Animal Society, as a stray in August 2020. Everyone at Mutts is excited for Daisy May to find her forever home.

Thanks to our amazing foster family and support system, Daisy is excelling and her socialization skills are coming along nicely. Just look at those eyes-you can tell she'll be eager to please her new family.

Daisy is inquisitive and loves to learn so a family that is excited to take her training to the next level would be ideal for her so she can really blossom into the dog she is meant to be.


Quick Stats:
Nap vs. Playing: Loves naps a bit more than playing right now.
Food vs. Toys: Food is her favorite, she's very food motivated and is eager to learn new things.
Dogs vs. Humans: Interactions have gone ok with the other dogs in the home but she loves her humans LOTS!

Quick Report Card on the Basics:
They have been fostered with other dogs and have done well with their respectful canine friends. 
They have been fostered with cats but for now we don't recommend having a feline in her adoptive home. 
They are not being fostered with children but would likely do well with kids that know how to interact with dogs.

If Daisy May sounds like the dog you've been waiting for, please fill out our adoption application today!

animal.description:
Meet Abe!

Hey everyone, my name is Abe! I'm just an easy going, low maintenance dog who loves his human companions. I weigh about 63 pounds and I think I'm pretty close to being 11 years old. I was rescued from the SPCA in 2012 so that's why I'm unsure of my age. I still have a lot of spunk in me for an old fellow. My best friend is a 5 year old, 33 pound Australian Shepherd. We play and wrestle every single day. I prefer to be around dogs that are smaller than me and I think it's a lot of fun to chase after cats, so it may be best to keep me away from them. I currently have a tiny two year old human at home whom I adore. I am very gentle with him and show him lots of love. I know I would make any family very happy, whether they have children or not. I get excited when I get to go on car rides but I'm also perfectly content being a couch potato at home with my family. I like to think that I'm well behaved. I can tell you when I have to go outside, and I also know cool tricks like sit, stay, lie down and shake. Thunderstorms and loud noises can sometimes scare me, so I like to be around my human friends during those times. All in all, I'm a lovable guy who would love the opportunity to put a smile on your face and to be apart of the family.

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

Hi everyone, my name is Cookie! I am a very, very special girl.

I am estimated at about 4-5 years old. I was rescued from a hoarding situation so I am very slowly learning how to be a regular dog.

I am great with other dogs, especially small ones. They are perfect snuggle size for me! I get very stressed by children and need a home without them.

I am not potty trained and I am very scared of the great big outdoors. I sometimes use a pee pad but not every time. 

I am not a lap dog and do not enjoy being handled. I will come to you for pets when I want them but I am quite independent and am not a cuddler.

I am looking for a quiet home, preferably with other small dogs with someone who understands my need for space and accepts me as the adorable little mess that I am!

You can apply to adopt me here: https://www.dogsdeservebetterblueridge.org/adopt

animal.description:
Jacks is a six-year old larger Dachshund mix boy whose owner could no longer take care of him. He is around 25 lbs - a chunky boy. No young children! No male dogs either - ok with female dogs. We were told Jacks is housetrained, leash trained, & crate trained. He stayed in a fence and prefers indoors. He knows a few commands and lived with a bird. Now he is has been slightly testy with us at times so think it takes him a bit to warm up and feel comfortable and we are thinking his vision might also not be the best. That means he needs someone to go slow with him and let him feel confident in his new environment - not coming in putting your face in his and pushing him too fast. Jacks likes to play fetch.
ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00. This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
IMPORTANT - we respond to your emailed applications and queries via email back to you. Please make sure you have either added our email (hselco@bellsouth.net) to your contact list or that you routinely check your SPAM folder for our response just to be safe. If we do not receive a timely response we simply move on to another applicant.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description. This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net

animal.description:
**PLEASE READ MAX'S BIO THOROUGHLY BEFORE INQUIRING. ALL REQUIREMENTS MUST BE MET IN ORDER TO BE CONSIDERED. **





This is Max, our handsome little guy who needs a VERY specific home. Max is a 14 month old male Maltese/Terrier/ Poodle mix who is approximately 17lbs of pure cuteness! This little guy came to us as an owner surrender when they felt they no longer had the time to care for a puppy. Unfortunately Max did not have much socialization and it shows because he is a very nervous pup. He took almost 2 months in his foster home before we began to see any signs of trust. He still will not let us attempt to pick him up and it takes careful maneuvering to do so. He is also NOT GOOD AT ALL on leash and will definitely need work on this issue. He is a fast and very agile pup and will require a very active home that can eventually run and hike with him. He CANNOT be in a sedentary home. Max is a puppy still and we only place our young dogs and puppies in homes with another young dog. He cannot go into a home if the only other dog is an adult or senior. This boy is ENERGETIC, FAST, and VERY ROUGH. When Max gets comfortable with his dog friends and starts to play, well, he plays very rough and tough. He likes to play bite on the tail, legs, and ears and drag the other dog around. He likes to pounce on them out of nowhere. He likes to chase them. If your dog does not play like this or you don't think they would be comfortable with playing like this, then Max would not be a candidate. Due to his jittery and jumpy anxiety, he cannot go into a home with young children 12 years or younger. One thing to know is Max is still in the puppy chewing faze. He is slowly growing out of it, but we see that he still will pick up things in his mouth and chew on them. He has recently chewed on the corner of some outdoor furniture, so his new home MUST be puppy savvy and ok with "accidents" like this and not get upset. We DO NOT want him crated because his last owner kept him in a crate most of the day and it was very detrimental to him. Another main requirement for Max is that he MUST go into a home with a yard. He cannot be an apartment/condo type dog. This guys loves to run here there and everywhere! Max is not an easy dog to feed and it definitely has to do with issues in his last home and the lack of socialization. If you set a plate of food down, he will just stare at it and not eat. He needs a lot of coaxing and someone who is willing to work with that issue by hand feeding him so he can gain trust. We want him in a home that will continue to feed him the way we do and what we feed him. He needs a good high quality dry food along with adding some high quality wet food and some home cooking. Max is on the thinner side and needs a little bulking up. We see that his fur was sparse/thin in areas and we want someone to continue adding supplements to get his coat in good condition. Max is very agile and can jump easily and because he is fast we require a 3ft gate at the front door in the inside of the home. This is contractual and will prevent him from taking off each time the door is open /closed. This is required regardless if you have a secure screen door or a gated front yard. This little guy did not have the best life as a young puppy and that is why we are being so specific in his forever home....he deserves it and more. 


--Because of Max's insecurities, we are requiring at least 2-3 meet/greets before even deciding to go the next step. Max is in the Torrance area and if chosen to do a meet/greet, you must come down 2-3 separate occasions with everyone in the household, including your dog to get to know him.

Max's adoption fee is $550


WE ONLY ADOPT IN LOS ANGELES AND SURROUNDING AREAS AS AN INPERSON HOME CHECK AND TRIAL PERIOD ARE REQUIRED.


If you meet all the requirements and would like an application, please contact us at 310-990-2020 or at Gina@theforgottendog.org

animal.description:
MADDIE is waiting to charm her way into your heart. Maddie would make an excellent outdoor adventure companion and adores going on long hikes with her foster family. Inside, she is a great big spoon or little spoon as the weather gets colder, and loves nothing more than snuggling up to her humans in any way she can. Her foster parents say she’s a couch potato 80% of the time!

Maddie is about 3 years old and 45 pounds. She has been doing fantastic in her foster home with learning tricks, commands and socializing with humans and other dogs with slow proper introductions. She is EXCELLENT on her recall skills and always comes running back when called. On a leash, Maddie gets hyper focused and pulls to play with other dogs/chase squirrels, so a calmer more suburban environment would be more ideal for her. She would do best in a home with experienced large breed handlers and no other animals. Maddie has been absolutely wooing her foster family with snuggles and her charm, and everyone who’s met her has fallen in love with her. Maddie is up to date on vaccies, crate and potty trained.

Check out the previous video: https://www.instagram.com/p/CHtCJuejn34/ to see all the tricks that Maddie has learned! Maddie's ideal home would be with someone with previous large breed dog expreiece and no other dogs.

This precious girl cannot wait to find a forever family of her own who will continue to provide her with structure and training. Could it be you? 


Apply to adopt at rescuecity.nyc/adopt! 


We are currently facilitating safe adoptions with COVID-19 protocols and adopt out to NYC and surrounding states only - NY CT PA & NJ. 

(We will consider other nearby states for adoption on a case by case basis. You must be willing to travel Brooklyn, NY to finalize the adoption.)

**If a dog is listed on petfinder as available then we are still accepting applications for that dog. We urge you to apply as soon as possible to be considered to adopt the dog you’re interested **

Thank you for wanting to give one of our adoptables a loving home! Please follow us on Instagram at @rescuecity for more adoptable updates!

animal.description:
Rufus is a 3-year-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, 4dx/heartworm tested, and neutered. This dog is also tested with other dogs, kennel-trained, and housebroken. We would love for you to meet this dog and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to CDC's recommended COVID-19 protocols, we are highly encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. If meeting in person, our foster homes are encouraged to wear masks, socially distance, and choose an outdoor meeting spot. Should you want to proceed forward with the adoption, all adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions. ***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
Gracie arrived in rescue very pregnant. Sadly after an emergency c section we lots all but one baby. 

Since then she has been busy nurturing and loving that one pup. 

So being able to get a true read on how she is with other dogs has been difficult. 

She lives in a foster home with other dogs and can see and hear them. But because of nursing she has no interest in meeting them. 

A meet with another dog in the home would be required and we do not think she will be friendly with other female dogs. 

She did ignore the shelter cat prior to arriving in rescue. 

She currently lives with 2 little girls and adores them. 

She is very snuggly and sweet with people and prefers to be close to her humans. 

She was a throw away momma who is ready for a forever home. 

She is estimated to be 1 and 2 years old

animal.description:
Beau's stats 01/23/21

AUSTIN ADOPTIONS ONLY
2 years old 25 lb male
Blue Heeler mix

POOR, POOR BEAU! Our boy is a Heeler mix who has come to us practically starved. His owners were no longer able to care for him and relatives said they would but neglected him terribly. He is around 15 pounds underweight, his hips are protruding and his spine and ribs are visible. Also, is heart worm positive and it breaks our hearts. It may take us awhile to figure out his placement needs. 

Beau's adoption fee of $350.00 includes Vet exams, current vaccinations, flea treatment, fecal and heart worm test, both are positive. He is being treated for fecal parasites and will be treated for heart worms one he gains some weight. He will be neutered and microchipped.

If you live in the Austin area and are interested in adopting, please go to www.ForgottenFriendsTX.org and fill out an application. 

Please be aware that we rarely have information on our dogs being good with cats as most of our foster homes don't have them. 

Adoption decisions are based on the best overall match and not done on a first-come-first-serve basis.

animal.description:
Meet Wilma!  
3 years old, female
35 lbs, brindle

This beautiful, petite girl is looking for a special family who will love all her endearing qualities.  Her ears stick up when she is feeling happy and confident or curious. She has a HUGE smile and gives the biggest goober face when she's excited, she loves snuggling and getting cozy, she grooms herself like a cat, wiggles while she walks, and definitely bonds with her "people" once she's decided you're one of them, and is definitely the type to gaze up at you lovingly!

Wilma is crate trained, house trained and has been through a training program.  She is eager to please and cooperates with clear boundaries.  She is a smart girl who knows many basic commands, and loves treat puzzle toys to keep her stimulated.  Because she is dog selective, Wilma will need to be the only dog in the home.  Her leash manners are a work in progress,  but would love hikes and other outdoor activities.  Will would do best in a home without cats and with older children.   If you think Wilma would be the perfect addition to your home, you can apply at www.carolinaadoptabulls.com/adopt

animal.description:
Maeve is a 1.5-2 year old husky/shepherd mix with big antenna ears that are soft as can be, and a goofy toothy grin. She is kennel trained and enjoys her ‘den’ when it’s time to go to sleep. Maeve is potty trained - we are also trying to train her to ring bells when she needs let out. She knows the sit, ‘go to kennel’, and responds to her name (recalls) fairly well. Maeve is a bit independent but don’t let that fool you - she is a cuddle monster. At first she may seem a bit picky with food but given time she will eat her meals and be more treat motivated. Maeve is good with other dogs and enjoys going to the doggy park. She also likes to play wrestle with her foster brother (cat) and sister (dog). Maeve still has a bit of puppy energy in her and will need her forever family to commit to professional training, as she is still learning some of the basic commands and tends to jump for attention. Because of this, she would do best in a home without small children and with a tall fully fenced yard. She is a gorgeous girl and melts hearts with her sweet kisses and full body wiggles. Please submit an application if you’re interested in snuggles with a cute blonde!

Our adoption fee is $260 for dogs over 5 months of age and includes all vaccinations, spay/neuter, micro chip implantation and registration/transfer, heartworm test and much more. Puppies up to 5 months of age are $275 and this includes all sets of puppy vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip implantation and registration and more. To adopt, go to www.fosterpetoutreach.org to complete an application.
Please note: Foster Pet Outreach tries to limit our adoptions to an area within approximately 60 miles of Peoria, Illinois.

animal.description:
From my foster:
Stella is a sweet girl! Super treat motivated and will work for food! Her tail wags so hard from excitement that's it hard to not give in.

Command based training has been going fairly well. Sit is well understood, and she pretty much goes potty on command (very important to me). She's fairly typical for dogs in respect to where she goes in the yard, frequently in the same areas, so she's a creature of habit. At feeding, she's just now starting to understand that I get to put the food down without her face in the bowl... and oh my does she drool! On command she eats, I do 3 cups daily, 1.5c/feeding and she does well with that. She is very diurnal - at sunrise she wants to be fed, at first dark she wants to be fed, and this borders on demanding for this schedule.

In the car she's fantastic and observant. She likes sitting up and watching everything that happens. She doesn't do much with her head out the window, but she's very observant.

On walks, in the beginning she can tug or pull you along in her direction and focus. Once she's content that she's out walking she starts to listen a lot better. Heeling is very difficult, but with good repeated training she'll improve. So far she's not shot off after other dogs on walks, though when in proximity of 10ft she can pull very strongly. Her focus is her focus; I've not successfully pulled her focus away from something she wants to pay attention to, so she's very stubborn on that level. Best of course is just stay a street width away when she often doesn't notice or that distance is just too much effort for her to care too much.

My recommendations would be for an owner who has had dogs before, as a first dog she'll probably walk all over the owner with her stubbornness. Everyone's different, but she'll need a lot of patience and someone who will set boundaries full time for the rest of her life. She learns very slowly, and I can somewhat see that she'll fall out of it if relaxed. She sometimes has a guilty look when she's done something she thinks might be questionable... it's kinda cute and makes me wonder what happens sometimes. She also has ready command of her front paws. She'll scratch at doors or try to move barriers that block her way if she wants to be on the other side. She also dreams; loudly.

Crate training hasn't been splendid but isn't terrible. Since I only have 1 bed that fits well, and that's the bed I keep in my office, I often have to move it so I'm a little lazy admittedly. She readily goes in, but she clearly doesn't like being alone most of all. She'll dig at the corner, but as of yet hasn't tried to break through the cage so that's something to watch for. Since I have a camera with audio, usually when she's getting a little rowdy I'll get on the speaker and tell her to settle down and she'll look confused, but then eventually calm down... maybe even lay down, but not very willingly.

Given I've been home a lot and she's very often with me she's kinda spoiled with company honestly. :)

Stella is best in an only dog home! She rather have all the attention to herself! We don't think she would share attention with cats either.

Let's help her find a home!! She is a very sweet girl, also spent over 4 months at a local shelter until Hopalong came in!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.=========================================================
Please contact app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .
Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

animal.description:
“Happiness is anyone and anything at all that’s loved by you” - Peanuts 

Linus the 9 year old Lhasa Apso mix came into our rescue in Senior September as an owner surrender. He is ready to start accepting applications and look for his forever home. 

He is a funny guy that sneezes and moans when he wants attention and loves to be silly and roll around on his back when he is excited. Linus has excellent leash manners and knows some basic commands such as place, heel, and off. He is very food motivated and regularly tries to convince his foster that he hasn’t had dinner yet. He is crate trained, muzzle trained, and has done well with potty training. 

Linus came to us with a history of using his teeth in situations that made him uncomfortable such as going to the groomer and guarding resources such as people’s laps. 

We have worked with him extensively on these things and he is now able to go to his groomer without issues and he knows how to get off of laps on command when sharing the couch with multiple people. He is also only allowed up when invited. 

He has been fostered in a home with other animals and does okay with calm, neutral dogs however he would prefer to be the only dog in the home. He’s not a fan of cats. Due to him having used his teeth in the past we will not be placing him in a home with children. 

He’s a cute, quirky boy that will thrive in a home that will give him lots of love as well as keeps up with his training and will provide structure and routine. His activity needs are low but he enjoys a daily walk. 

Linus is neutered, up to date on vaccines, neg hw test, and is up to date with preventatives. He is being fostered in Bloomington, Indiana. We are seeking a home for him within an hour of Bloomington, Indiana. His adoption fee is $150.

Please fill out an initial application if you are interested in him. 

https://forms.gle/hmA2LKTxn3hSMdST6

Larry wants out of the shelter ASAP and needs your help!

We are seeking a foster or adoptive home for this sweet anxious guy to get him back into a home environment as soon as possible... please fill out an adoption or foster application on our website www.rbari.org or email dogkennel@rbari.org if you can help him 

Poor Larry was adopted as a puppy and just returned when his owner lost his home and was forced to move in with relatives where no pets were allowed. He is devastated and very stressed being back in the shelter after so long in a real home and is hoping his stay will be short!

Larry was not socialized around other dogs and needs to be an only pet in an adult home. He's a friendly strong energetic guy who craves attention, structure, and training and a quieter home environment away from the barking dogs in the kennel. 

Please share his adorable face and help him find a place to call home, even temporarily, ASAP! Primary Color: Tan Age: 5yrs 3mths 0wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description:
Meet Regal Roo!

Roo is a gorgeous, mostly Thai Ridgeback mix hailing from the island of Koh Samui with a very sad history:  born on the street to a feral mom, she and her sister Lulu were the only 2 surviving pups from a litter of 6. Thankfully, Roo and her sister are okay and her mom has also been sterilized and continues to be fed and cared by their rescuer. Roo is now in Toronto and settling into her new life and she loves the snow! 

Roo is just under a year old (born March 2020) and still has lots of that that puppy-ness about her (good and bad!). She is inquisitive about everything, happy, friendly and easy-going. She loves other dogs and currently lives with 3 others with no issue. She can still be a destructive chewer and needs to be supervised. She loves her walks, is fine in the car and at the vet. She has settled into life with her foster family in the east end of Toronto fabulously.

Roo is incredibly sweet, smart and loves to snuggle. She has already mastered her basic commands, knows the word treat and will occasionally take herself to the treat cupboard and tap it with her nose (she may be a bit too smart for her own good). She is also very active and athletic with zero fear of heights and has no issues trying to climb things, so a secure backyard with a high fence is a must for this girl. She also needs a family that will give her sufficient physical and mental stimulation, she's got that intelligent, working dog thing. She would love advanced obedience and a tricks and/or agility class.

Roo weighs about 17.5 kilos, she may still have a bit of growing and filling out to do. She's housetrained, fully vetted, spayed, current on vaccinations (boosters just administered in Canada), 4Dx negative and micro-chipped. Roo is also crate trained. She will fuss initially, but settles quickly and will rest quietly in her crate for several hours. She would be fine as an only dog or with fur sibs. Due to her age, size and breed mix, no cats or young kids; dog-savvy kids 12+ would be fine as she loves to play and has loads of energy. Roo is available for adoption in the GTA only. This regal girl is a real treasure! Her adoption fee is 1500. 00. If you think you are a good match for Ms. Roo, we would love to hear from you! Please visit our website for more information and to download an application form.

animal.description:
Prudence is a 3-4 year old, mixed breed dog who weighs 37 pounds. You can tell that Pru's previous owner didn't take very good care of her! He skin was a nasty mess but is healing well. She has completed treatment for heartworm and is now ready to find a family that will take good care of her forever! She is a tad shy at times but is really happy and active once she settles in. She has been non-reactive with other dogs and is fine with kids who are big enough not to be knocked over by her! We have not exposed her to cats. 

Augusta Dog Adoptions is an all- volunteer, foster- based rescue. We take applications online and are scheduling individual adoptions in the Waynesboro, VA area during the pandemic.  A $175.00 adoption fee ($300 for puppies under 6 months old) helps us take care of all the dogs we rescue. All dogs are spayed/neutered, tested for heartworm and tick borne diseases (if old enough), microchipped, and vaccinated for rabies (if old enough), distemper/parvo and bordetella. They are also treated for internal and external parasites. Many dogs also receive extensive medical care such as dental work and major surgeries. For more information and to apply to adopt, please visit www.augustadogadoptions.org

animal.description:
Shelby needs a home with:
- no apartments, condos or townhomes
- a fully fenced yard
- no children under the age of 12
- no chickens 

Meet Shelby! Shelby is a gorgeous 7 year old Labrador Retriever/Border Collie mix with a sweet and lovable personality. This cutie absolutely loves to go for walks and sniff every exciting new scent she can find. She walks well on a leash, and would be happy to be your adventure girl - she'll show you how to truly enjoy life by stopping and smelling all the flowers along the way. She would enjoy nose work such as snuffle mats and other fun scent-focused games. She'll show off her goofy personality as she zooms around the yard and chases after plush toys and tennis balls. While she doesn't have the full game of fetch down, she absolutely loves to pounce after a toy and fling it around in the air - it's adorable (she just needs to learn to bring it back!). Shelby is a smarty pants and can definitely learn lots of new tricks and skills. She knows how to 'sit' and 'shake,' and can even catch a treat right out of the air. Shelby needs a home (no apartments, condos or townhomes please) with a securely fenced in yard and will need to be supervised at all times. She is a super smart pup who loves to go on adventures on her own- she has figured out how to open doors and gates, so she needs to be closely managed in her home. Shelby is looking for a home without children under the age of 12 (too overwhelming), and without chickens. She may do best in a home without cats. Shelby has lived with dogs before and does well with calm dogs. Shelby has a history of seizures and is currently on medication to help, which seems to be working well! Her adopters will need to be prepared to work with their own full-service vet to manage this in their home. Shelby can be stressed being left alone and is on medication to help with her anxiety. She would do best in a home with an adopter who is home often and can work with a trainer to help her overcome her anxiety. Shelby is ready for a forever home of her own - if you're ready make her part of your family, submit an application today!

If you're interested in adopting Shelby, please email a completed adoption application to adoptions@kitsap-humane.org. Adoption applications and more information about our adoption process can be found on our website here: https://www.kitsap-humane.org/adopt/how-to-adopt/. Once your application has been received, you will be placed in line to have your application reviewed. All applicants are pre-screened over the phone, and then are scheduled for a time to come in and meet the dog at the shelter.

animal.description:
NO dogs
NO cats
NO children under 16 yrs of age.
Chihuahua experienced home needed 

My name is SOPHIE. I came to Rhodie’s Rescue after the nice family I am staying with saved me from the streets. Because my family never came looking for me, my friends at Rhodie’s are helping me to find the best new family who will keep me safe and love me forever! 
They tell me I look like a long haired chihuahua or possibly a Papillion or Russian Toy mix. We won’t know for sure without DNA testing, but one thing is for sure... I’m super cute!! 
I’m about 3-4 yrs of age and pretty tiny at about 5-6lbs. But don’t let my size fool you! I can be a sassy girl when I feel like it! My friends tell me I have a ‘Chihuahua attitude’ so they feel my new family should be familiar or have experience with Chihuahuas as to handle my attitude. I’m not really sure why, but I will growl when you pick me up, or pretty much anytime I’m feeling sassy! I’ve never snapped or but anyone, but there’s always the possibility that could come next if you don’t handle me correctly. That’s why my friends and foster family don’t want me to be in a home with kids. 
I’m like other dogs, but I’m pretty dominant around other dogs. I will stand on my hind legs and place my front paws on them and growl/bark. I also chase them and nip at their legs when they are running... I sometimes think I’m a tough big dog, and my current foster siblings ‘put up’ with me, but I will definitely get hurt if another dog retaliates after I have been provoking them... so my friends say I need to be an only dog in my new home, but I can definitely join my doggie friends for a walk or play date. 
I love to sit on laps and cuddle. I’m a pretty good kisser too, and it’s hard to resist me! 
I like to run and play, and going on leash walks is my favorite thing to do! 
I know not to potty in the house, but sometimes I get excited and tinkle a little. I sleep in a crate, but I would really prefer to sleep in bed with you! 
I love my humans and hope my new family is home to spend lots of time with me, and active enough to keep up with my energy while playing and never miss my daily walks I look so forward to! 
My adoption fee is $350 which includes health examination, current vaccinations, spay, microchip, flea and deworming treatment along with any other medical or dental deemed necessary by our veterinarian.

animal.description:
Have you met Chopstix?

5-year-old Chopstix came to us on July 3, 2020 from a hoarding situation that resulted in uncontrolled breeding and 60 very similar looking dogs. Choppy has cerebellar hypoplasia, an underdeveloped brain stem impacting his motor function. This means Chopstix can't walk or stand for more than a few seconds and wobbles his way around. Despite this, Choppy is the sweetest, happiest little floof! He has a huge heart and is so determined. He has been working with a physical therapist who volunteers at FFF and making progress using wheels to aid in his mobility. (Be sure to watch the video!)

Choppy has a big fan club, and a FFF volunteer who has neuro dogs of her own, takes him on outings nearly every weekend. They've gone boating, swimming, and hiking, just to name a few! She shared, "I'll be honest, I spent a lot of time thinking about the things I could write about Choppy and what makes him wonderful. I could hit the usual beats and say he's adorable, he's sweet and loving, he always wants to play, and even though he can't walk, he loves to sit in his carrier and go on adventures. I could add that he spent 5 years of his life in a neglectful situation, likely never knowing real human affection and care. I could add that he gets the gist of peeing and pooping outside, and that he's a friend to cats. But I could say this about SO many dogs, all deserving of forever homes, and it wouldn't capture what makes Choppy so special to me (and what I hope will one day make him special to his future family).

I also thought about what might stop people from taking Choppy home. I will be totally honest with anyone who asks - Choppy will be more work than your average dog. His cerebellar hypoplasia is significant enough that he can't walk and sometimes needs a little help doing the day-to-day tasks that other dogs don't even have to think about doing. That means help getting around, helping standing up to pee/poo, and sometimes a little assist while eating. But oh man - when that little golden fluffy face looks at you and nuzzles into your chest in gratitude and in love, there's no feeling like it."

Dogs with cerebellar hypoplasia

can be a lot of work, but it is oh-so-rewarding. Think

you might be up for it? Apply to meet Chopstix:
www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Apply to become a family: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated: 1/31/21 KG

This puppy is in Tennessee. Adoption Donation $250 if picked up in TN, $300 plus transport fee for out of state adoptions.

Meet Miss Athena! She is a 6-month-old, 21 pound Labrador Retriever/Mountain Cur mix (best guess) with a shiny black coat. Athena enjoys playtime and is always up for a game of chase or tug. She gets along great with other dogs and cats too. Athena would do her best in an active home where she can get lots of interaction. She is eager to please and treat motivated. Athena is doing well with crate training and working hard on her other obedience skills and needs a new family who is ready to continue her training. She is a touch timid when she first meets new people and in new places but warms up once she knows you are all about fun and affection. If you are seeking a sweet, medium-sized canine companion to add to your heart and home, apply to adopt Athena today!

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website: http://aarf-tn.com/adopt/adoption-apps/

If you have questions that are not covered in the profile, visit the Pet Inquiry Form: http://aarf-tn.com/contact/pet-inquiry-form/.

THIS PET IS FOSTERED IN TENNESSEE! We do list and adopt our pets nationwide. Typical transport cost to the Northeast is $160. Due to interstate adoption regulations, we are not able to adopt to RI and MA state residents.

A.A.R.F. (All About Rescue and Fixin' Inc.) http://aarf-tn.com/ is a non-profit, 501(c)(3) no kill animal rescue organization located in the Upper Cumberland area of Tennessee. A.A.R.F. is comprised of unpaid volunteers and survives only on public donations. Thank you for thinking adoption first!

Prior to adoption, all canines and felines are spayed or neutered, have received their age appropriate vaccinations, have been de-wormed for common parasites, and have received treatment for prevention of fleas and ticks. All canines over the age of 6 months have been tested for heartworm. All canines are put on heartworm prevention as soon as possible - this means dogs as soon as they are tested negative. Puppies are put on prevention immediately. All felines, regardless of age, have been tested for Feline Leukemia/FIV. Each animal receives a health check by a licensed veterinarian prior to adoption. Anything else found will be treated by our organization prior to adoption.

animal.description:

She would love an attached secure fenced yard and someone to keep her entertained and challenged during the day as she is one smart curious girl. animal.description: Angel is a one and a half year old shepherd mix that is looking for a great new home. Angel is fully vetted and weighs about 40 pounds. She loves to go for long walks, play fetch and do all the agility equipment at the shelter.  She is not a big fan of other dogs so will need to your one and only.  Probably not a match for cats either.  She will need a household where children are significantly older and know how to interact appropriately with high energy dogs.  She is house-trained.

By the way, she is spayed, microchipped, and current on all shots -- all ready for a new home.

For more information about me, please call the Douglas County Animal Care and Services (DCACS) at 775-782-9061 or the Douglas Animal Welfare Group (DAWG) at 775-267-7325. Or come meet her at the Douglas County Animal Shelter (please call first to make sure I'm still at the shelter). Click on Douglas Animal Welfare Group below for the address and directions.

ALSO A "MEET AND GREET" WILL BE REQUIRED IF THERE ARE ANY OTHER DOGS IN THE HOUSEHOLD. 

ONE LAST THING! If you rent, you will be required to provide written approval from your landlord that you can have a dog. It needs to be specific, i.e. all dogs okay, no big dogs, specific breeds restricted, etc.

animal.description:
Happy Birthday Gary Groot!My siblings and I decided to sponsor this life saving transport to honor our father's 81st birthday. Our father, Gary Groot, is the main reason we are all animal lovers. We grew up watching and learning how to properly pamper our puppies and he instilled in us the importance of adoption; how it saves lives. My father just lost his beloved Precious who he loved with all his heart and took her everywhere, even bought a travel trailer so she could join him on mission projects for the church. Precious was by his side for the last 15 years and will now wait for him at the Rainbow Bridge. Suzanne, Karen & Tom
Karen and her siblings were born around September 7, 2020, and may top out in the 65-75 pound range when done growing. These adorable furballs look a lot like GSD and Husky pups but there could be several breeds mixed in as well. They are happy, active, social, pups and they are ready to find their perfect forever homes!
The Adoption Fee for this dog is $550.00
Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general our fees include spay/neuter, all age appropriate vaccines, Home Again micro-chipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY.

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES

We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption.

Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

Online Application

animal.description:
Kaia (Ky-a) is a 5 month old Catahoula/Shepherd/Retriever mix.

 

Kaia is an amazing, social and highly intelligent sweetheart of a dog. She has been well loved in her current home for over three months; but they have come to the heartbreaking conclusion that they are not the best fit for her at this time. The decision was made out of care and for the success of Kaias future; hoping that her forever family will have the time, resources and environment to give Kaia the proper training, socialization and consistency to bring out all of her amazing qualities. 

 

Kaia would do best in a home with older, dog-savvy children who understand not to overwhelm her as she develops and learns through her training. With Kaias incredible smarts and energy we believe an experienced home with a yard she can run and grow in would be a great fit. Kaia is playful, loves to run, go on walks and loves to be around people. We'd love to find an active family that appreciates and flourishes Kaias intelligence. 

 

We cannot wait for this special girl to live up to her true potential in her forever home.

 

Some other notes about Kai:


	
	Kaia is completely crate trained at night 
	
	
	Knows sit 
	
	
	Knows Stay 
	
	
	Knows Give me your paw
	
	
	Know Leave it

animal.description:
This little girl was found by a Good Samaritan. She was acting weird, so they took her to the vet. What they discovered makes us absolutely sick to our stomach. This little 14 lb dog was overdosing on methamphetamine. The veterinarian gave her medicine to get the drugs out of her system and bring her out of her high, but she is now blind. She also has a funny walk, but it just adds to her cuteness! She is about 6 years old and is a Chihuahua/Pekingese/Mini Dachshund/Pomeranian mix. Although Indie is now blind, she is not letting her situation get her down and is a happy and super sweet girl! She is now fully vetted and ready to find her forever home! Her ideal home would be without young children. Although she loves everyone, she needs a home that is free of toys and obstacles. She would be fine in a home with a laid back small dog or even without another dog. She is currently in a foster home with other dogs and just co-exists with them. Occasionally she will try to play with them, but doesn't really understand how to play. She has a halo, which she wears in a new environment for the first day or two, but then she gets around just fine without it. She needs someone that is home or works from home most of the time. She sleeps in her kennel at night and doesn't make a peep. She is potty trained, but needs you to guide her with noises out to the backyard. No apartments please, it is not safe for her to do stairs and the commotion of a lot of different people and dogs would be overwhelming to her. 

If you would like to adopt a dog from Rescue Row please fill out an application at https://form.jotform.com/91767055990166 

*Please check your junk email folder if you do not receive a response from a Rescue Row member within 48 hours.

*You must live within an hour of the DFW Metroplex because we do trial adoptions and require a homecheck

*Our adoption fees are as follows (paid by cash or a check made out to Rescue Row):

 Dogs 12 weeks-6 months old: $300 adoption fee

 Dogs 7 months and older: $275 adoption fee

Rescue Row is a 501(c)3 (non-profit) all volunteer dog rescue organization serving the DFW Metroplex. We are dedicated to rescuing dogs in shelters, dogs in abusive or neglectful situations, and dogs surrendered by their owners because of difficult circumstances. We place dogs in loving, responsible, committed permanent homes, following a comprehensive adoption process, which includes taking considerable care in finding good matches and educating prospective adopters about the responsibilities and costs of bringing a dog into their homes and lives. Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, microchipped, receive all appropriate veterinary care and treatment, and placed in nurturing foster homes while they await placement in their permanent homes. We assist dogs in distress without regard to age, breed or ease of placement. Dogs in the greatest need take priority. Finally, we strive to work with shelters and other rescue and humane organizations to develop a network of supporters and volunteers in order to create a better world for homeless dogs.

Striker is a 11 week young, lab mix puppy, he came from Houston TX! Hes currently getting over a really bad rash but his skin is healing nicely and his fur is coming in so smooth. He is completely potty trained for the backyard but will use a potty pad indoors in case of emergencies. He is sooo smart and is catching on great to the normal daily routine. He is great at taking his medicine and getting special baths. Hes got the cutest black and brown cheeks with spots of black all over, with a mostly white coat. He has the cutest little black mask on with an adorable little spotted nose He has this awesome Mohawk on his neck, so unique. He is the sweetest boy and deserves a wonderful forever home. Does yours sound like the perfect fit?

I need a single family home since I am pittie! I can NOT go to a home in a city or county with pitbull restrictions.

I am heartworm positive. Heartworm is NOT contagious. The rescue covers the cost of treatment at the rescue's vet. 

Sweet Marshall is a 4 year old Staffordshire Terrier x. He appears to have Pitbull in him. 
Hes a small guy standing about 16 at the shoulders. We nicknamed him Meatball because, well, it just fits. This cutie will follow you around the house. He will do just about anything you ask as he just wants to make you happy. He learned sit, stand, lay, and down within the first few days in foster. 

He loves people and no one is a stranger to him. He got along well with other large/ medium sized dogs both male and female. We are unsure about small dogs. He needs to be in a home without a cat.

Marshall walks great on a leash. He doesnt pull at all and loves his daily walks. 
Marshall doesnt really know how to play so you have to show him, then he will follow your lead.

He was recently neutered and had a few incidents with marking in the house. We remedied this by crate training. So the first few days you may have to remind him not to mark by crating him. This isnt a big deal though, because he really does love his crate. 

Get your application in soon because this guy will be adopted quickly. He captured my heart. He is the goodest boy and is just waiting to find his forever family.

animal.description:
Sadie is an amazing dog! She is a German Shepherd/Aussie mix, and just about 3-4 years old, and 40lbs. Sadie is amazing with children (even babies!) and adults - all people in general. She is also fully potty trained, and leash trained. She does not need to be crated, as she never chews anything up. Sadie is currently in foster care with 4 small children (two under a year old and two 5 years old) and does amazing with them! She is very sweet and friendly and gentle.

Sadie was never properly socialized with dogs, so she doesn't know how to get along with other dogs. She will bark (on leash) when she sees another dog, and since she is leash reactive, her foster has never wanted to try her off leash with dogs. We think given time, training, and slow introductions, she should be able to overcome it with an adopter willing to work with her. We would love to find her a home where she is the only dog, and ideally with someone less active, and with a large yard or acreage for Sadie to have for exercise and play.

The following is written about her by her current foster: Please read it all before inquiring about Sadie!
•••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••
“Sadie has been friendly and calm around all people since the day we picked her up. She has even done very well when around my two 10 month old grandsons (pictured) and my two 5 year old grandsons. She doesn’t mind them petting her or sitting with her. She often lays near them while they are playing. She has been left at home alone several times for maybe 3 hours max and has done well – as long as no food has been left on the kitchen counters. I always give her a Kong, snuffle mat or chew stick to distract her when I leave. Initially she would be excited/nervous when I left but she is much better now. Sadie sleeps in our bedroom with us – either in our walkin closet, on her bed or on the floor next to our bed. She only gets up on our bed in the morning when we awake.

Sadie was fully potty trained when we received her. She does not let us know when she needs out but since we have been home mostly she is in and out a lot during the day and this has not been an issue – she also seems to be able to “hold it” well. She very rarely will bark and then it only seems to be when she is surprised by something. When she sees other dogs she will whine and pull to go towards them. Unfortunately her overstimulation around dogs can become too much if they make contact, typically. Sadie walks well on the leash with her “no pull” harness. Sadie does very well traveling in the car on the back seat.

Sadie can get over a 4 foot fence or wall when she is motivated, so never leave her unattended in the yard. A 6 foot fence is a must! As long as she is entertained and engaging with someone, she has no reason to want to try to jump.

Sadie has been very trainable since we received her. She has learned the “sit” command and will typically stay sitting until I release her with the word “OK”. We have been working on learning “lie down”.

Sadie will play tug a war and will release the rope when asked to. She also will play fetch and will typically drop the ball when asked to do so. We have been working on her self control. When I feed her I ask her to sit before putting her bowl down. I put the bowl on the floor and she will stay sitting and not go for the food until I release her with “ok”. She does this quite well now. When she does something she is not supposed to I use the words “eh, eh” and she will typically stop or back off. When I call her by name she will typically respond right away and come to me. We have been working on “counter conditioning” her to get her to be more under control when seeing other dogs. She has definitely improved over the past 2 months and will sit and stay mostly calm – from a distance – as the dog/s go by. Her best training treat is anything cheese-flavored, which she loves!

She has been so calm and sweet with all people and even with my young grandsons. The problem is she gets too overstimulated when seeing other dogs, that it turns into wanting to go after them. She just can’t be around dogs. Someone who is retired and has a large yard would be perfect for her. I say this because keeping her from going on walks might be best -if you do, when walking on a path or trail and passing another dog you need to keep a good distance between them and a strong hand on her leash. Other than the “dog” issue she has been a great dog to have around.”
•••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••

We are searching for Sadie’s forever home with an individual or family who has no other pets, and can commit to working with Sadie’s issue of not being able to be around other dogs.

Sadie’s adoption fee is $200 and that will include a harness, food, treats, toys, all of her shots, and her spay.

If you are interested in being this loving girl’s forever home, please fill out an application here: https://farfels.com/farfels-rescue/adoption-form/

animal.description:
The state puppies are 8 of the cutest and fattest little fur balls you will ever see!

We rescued their mama Cali (and her pregnant daughter Molly) from the streets of Tijuana. A Good Samaritan took them in temporarily while his friends tried to find a rescue. We were so lucky to find them!

Cali is an incredible mama. She is sweet and attentive, but sometimes prefers that visitors give her all the attention! We’re guessing she’s a cattle dog pit mix, although none of her pups have her coloring. We’re guessing (which is a rough guess as this early stage) that they will weigh about 50-70 pounds when fully grown.

There are 6 boys (Texas Dakota Alaska Hawaii Kansas and Tennessee) and 2 girls (Georgia and Montana). They’re just three weeks old and wouldn’t be ready to go home for another few weeks, but we wanted to post them to give potential adopters a chance to meet them at this incredible stage. 

Our adoption fee is 750 and includes all three rounds of puppy vaccines (including a neo natal Parvo vaccine for added immunity), full health checks before being adopted, deworming, and having them fixed and microchipped with snpla around 6 months old.

Please download an application from our website, or shoot us an email if you’re interested in the state pups.

Thank you!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Heller mix/ female / 20lbs/ Adoption fee $450Hello! My name is Frances and I can't wait to find the perfect forever-family to call my very own. What am I looking for? Well, cuddles, treats, fun and gamesall the things a puppy loves!

I'm very sweet and gentle-natured, but I'm also full of puppy spirit and I appreciate a good game of "Steal Your Slippers" or "Tug On Your Pant Leg." I love the snow and racing around in circles in the yard. I'm very adventurous outside and enjoy climbing snow drifts, chasing leaves, and fetching little sticks.

But all that energy wears a good girl out! I love to get scooped up for kisses and then settle in on the couch for a movie and a nap. I hang out quietly in my kennel near foster mom during the day while she works from home. I nap and play with toys until she lets me out for a break. And I'm pretty good at night too - making it six or more hours before letting you know it's time to potty. I'm a fast learner and haven't had any accidents in my kennel so far; and only a couple in the house - oops, sorry!

I have two adult dog foster sisters, and I LOVE them so much! I love to wrestle and play tug and chase with them - I'm sure I'd love to have a doggie brother or sister in my new home.

I really think I'm the perfect puppy and will grow up to be the BEST girl! If that's what you're looking for, then I can't wait to meet you!

XOXO - Frannie

The adoption fee covers the cost of the animal's spay/neuter surgery, microchipping, FIV/FeLK testing (for cats) or Heartworm Testing (for dogs), deworming and all core age appropriate vaccinations. animal.description:
Meet June! This darling Terrier mix puppy is looking for a family to call her own! June is a sweet, shy gal who quietly greets everyone she meets with a gentle tail wag. June enjoys spending her days exploring all the sniffs there are to find on her neighborhood walks, and patrolling for squirrels in the backyard. She would be a great companion on weekend trips to the lake, or hiking on nature trails throughout the area. 

June is looking for a family who enjoys activity and exercise as much as she does. When not going on adventures with her person, June happily romps around the yard, playing with toys - stuffed toys are particularly fun! She loves to chase thrown toys, but is still learning how to bring them back! 

June is working hard on learning all the things "good dogs" need to know - like leash manners and sitting when asked - and would love for her new family to continue her manners training. This smart girl is treat motivated, and eager to please! June enjoys the company of other dogs, and would love to have a playmate or two in her forever home.

Her foster reports, "She's very sweet and loving and she LOVES her treats. She also loves to cuddle and will give hugs (of sorts) if you kneel down to greet her." June can be nervous about meeting new people, and will do best in a home, with older children, that will give her the time (and tasty treats!) she needs to make new friends. If you are looking for an active, fun loving companion, June is the one for you - schedule an adoption appointment today!

To learn more about June, watch this video: https://youtu.be/ihDs6tedlGM

He is great with other dogs and kids. He is a super sweet boy and travels well in a vehicle. He will need basic training, but he is an absolute lover and likes to give hugs. He is learning the crate, but does protest vocally but does settle down, so shared wall living would not be recommended. Rudy does like to chase squirrels, but has lived in a home with a dog saavy cat just fine. He is high energy, so small kids could get knocked over if he jumps up. A home that has a large fenced yard or acreage would be ideal for this boy who wants to greet everyone to say 'hello' and does not want to miss any activity happening outdoors. The stray hold, at the Toccoa-Stephens County Humane Shelter, is 5 days. That allows owners a fair amount of time to come looking for their pets. On the sixth day, the animal becomes the property of the Toccoa-Stephens County Humane Shelter and is offered for adoption. An animal may be pre-adopted, however, if the owner comes forward, within the 5 day stray hold, the animal goes back to the owner. The adoption fee is refunded at that time.
TSCHS Adoption Procedure
Adoption Fees: Adoption fee includes spay or neuter, current (age appropriate) vaccinations, and a microchip.
Hours of Operation:
 Tues.-Saturday, 11-6

Pricing:
 Dogs $100 - Puppies $125
 Senior dogs $60
 Cats $60 - Kittens $75
 Senior Cats $30

Contact Information:
Toccoa-Stephens County Humane Shelter
1747 Scenic Dr.
Toccoa, GA 30577
Phone: 706 282 3275
Fax: 706 886 7358
Email: Info@TSCHS.org

Adoption process:
 Fill out an application
 Fill out a contract
 Pay the adoption fee
*Stray animals may be Pre-adopted before the stray hold is up. If an owner comes forward, the adoption fee is returned to the adopter. If the owner does not come forward, the animal is scheduled to be altered. When that is done, the pet can go home with the adopter.
Unfortunately, we are not able to hold animals without the adoption process being completed.
That includes the payment of the adoption fee. Adoptions are done on a first come, first served basis. Applications can be emailed and payment can be made via phone and at WWW.PayPal.me/TSCHS.
Otherwise we can not hold animals. After the adoption fee has been paid, arrangements will be made to have the pet altered. No pets leave without being altered. Prather is a shelter favorite....but he is a beast! Unfortunately, as a puppy, he was never taught any manners. So now he is a maniac! But a very loveable maniac!
Prather is super smart and will make a really awesome pet for a dog savvy person.
Prather has small prey drive, so he can not live with any small animals. No small dogs, no cats! He would be too much for small children.

animal.description:
Meet Rocco! Rocco wants nothing more than to be loved. He adores people but can be standoffish around most people at first - with proper introductions, his desire for affection quickly wins out and he will be your best friend. You'll get to know his excitement by how vocal he can get and a rapid tail wag, but he quickly settles down. He does have minor food aggression behavior that is currently being worked on and he doesn't enjoy new friends hovering overhead. Due to this, he needs a home with no children (16+ is acceptable). He loves playing with toys and craves attention! He also loves head scratches and holding his paws in your hands. He is potty and crate trained; he enjoys being in his crate because it is his safe space. Rocco will start to chew if left unsupervised, but a kong ball works very well to keep him occupied. Rocco is not an expert at leash walking, but he tries his hardest to behave. At the start he may pull a little, but he has been previously trained with a prong collar to sense the added pressure and halt or move closer to you as the walks progresses. He can sit, lay down, and give paw(s). He is extremely loving and loves other dogs - he just wants to play! Since Rocco needs room to run and play, you must have a fenced in yard (at least 5 feet tall) to apply for Rocco. Rocco would also do best in an active home that will help him get his energy out and keep his mind stimulated.

Note: Rocco has been in 2 foster homes where he experienced no issues and truly thrived. When he has clear and firm boundaries, he learns to trust his owner and rely on them for guidance. He was adopted out twice to homes that unfortunately could not set these boundaries and establish themselves as the leader, which caused Rocco to take on that role and "rule the roost". He has completed board and train with our wonderful trainer who believes that he will thrive with someone who will exhibit strong leadership skills, patience, and understanding. Hes done amazing with our trainer and is ready for a foster or maybe even a forever home!

Once again, we must express that this goofy boy will need an experienced dog owner that will exhibit strong leadership skills. His trainer says, "He needs someone that is going to focus on rules and boundaries, the affection secondary. If you try affection primarily, he is going to rule the roost." With effective leadership, we know that this goofy boy will thrive and prove just how awesome of a dog he is!

Our adoption process for Rocco will consist of:
-completing our online application
-initial phone interview
-vet check (if applicant has existing pets)
-reference check
-home check (will be either in person or via facetime or zoom)
-final phone interview
-meet and greet
-In-home training sessions with our trainer once Rocco has settled in.

If you are interested in adopting Rocco, please fill out an application at lastdaydogs.com. If you have any questions, please send an email to adopt@totuanimalrescue.org

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Ramsey is a 1.5 year old Havanese poodle mix! Ramsey and his brother were surrendered to a local shelter in Texas Heartworm positive. Both boys have been successfully treated and are medically clear for adoption. They will need to remain on preventative for their lifetime which is fairly inexpensive depending on the brand you choose. They are otherwise healthy, happy boys!

Ramsey is a little lover. He is smart and active. He loves people more then anything and is very very cuddly. He wants nothing more then to be loved. He often times lays on the back of the couch so he can rest his head on your shoulder and if you stop petting him he has no problem using his paw to remind you to keep going. He is crate trained and does go outside to use the bathroom BUT he does also Mark inside! He is freshly neutered so we hope this improves but we can never guarantee that it will and we want to be perfectly honest about this! Please do NOT expect a house trained dog and please be willing to put in the time and effort to properly train him. He does wear a belly band without any issues and stands nicely for you to put it on. He has a doggy door and a fenced in yard at his foster home and does well with that set up.

Ramsey likes other dogs but he is very dominant with them. He also guards his food in the crate but he can take treats nicely in a group. He is crate trained but he will bark initially and cry sometimes when he is in it because he only wants to be with you. He does not have cats in his foster home so we have not tested him with them. He has been around children and has been totally loving to them. He is very well behaved for grooming and did wonderful for his bath.

Ramsey does bark sometimes when he is excited or when someone comes over or if he has been in the crate for a while but when he is out with his family he is generally pretty quiet. He likes to play with toys. He loves using the agility equipment in his foster home and is pretty good at it.

He is very agile, he likes to climb and jump. He has climbed baby gates and the chain link fence in his foster home chasing a squirrel therefore if you have a fence it will need to be a privacy fence. No invisible or electric fences. Ramsey is a great little dog. He is very submissive to humans and wants nothing more then to find a loving family of his own.

If you think Ramsey is a match for your family don't hesitate to apply!

Ramsey is neutered, up to date with vaccines, microchipped, flea/worm treated and treated for heartworm. His adoption fee is $450

animal.description:
Citrine cane to rescue from a SD reservation.  He was born on 8.6.2020.  He will be neutered by 6 months of age. He responds to the name of ASH and weighs 45#. He came to rescue with other puppies and his momma. His adoption fee is $350.00.

Hi! I’m Ash and I’m looking for my Furever home. If you are looking for a well-balanced, smart, and loving pup, I am your dog. My days consist of a lot of napping and playing with my older foster sister. She is also a shepherd mix. We like to chase each other. Do you have a brother or sister for me I can play with? That would be nice because when I am awake, I have a lot of energy. Give me some squeaky toys and I am set for life!   

When my humans leave me in my kennel, sometimes I cry and howl, but only when I’m left alone. I sleep really well in my kennel though, I sometimes cry at night but mainly because I need to go potty. They say I am a good boy and have taught me a ton!  My humans have taught me sit, down, stay, come, off, no, speak, “high five”, and heel. They also taught me how to ring a bell when I need to go potty,  but I like to stare at them instead of using it. They say I am potty trained. 

I had some issues with my tummy for a while, but I am on the mend. Just don't make too many sudden changes to my diet. With that being said, I am extremely food motivated, but I am learning my mealtime manners. Before I am fed, I must sit patiently before they say “ok”. 

 Please adopt me. I will be your best friend I paw-mise.   I love to chase bunnies but not sure if I would chase kitties.  I am good with children but because I am a puppy I sometimes will hip or jump on people of all ages..  I need a 6' high fenced yard so I can get lots of exercise and a sister or brother to burn some energy.  

Our dogs are not allowed to be left in a yard 24/7 unattended. They must live in the house with humans, not tied, chained, tethered or confined on a tie our of any sort.  We do not recommend an electronic underground fence system for shepherds.  Please go to www.faerielandrescue.org if you are serious about this puppy.

animal.description:
"She is a solo act." Runcie is a sweet, petite four and half-year-old Great Pyrenees mix. She is beautiful with her white coat and gorgeous dark markings on her face. Runcie weighs about 55 lbs and has a good appetite. She makes friends instantly with people.

Runcie is house trained, not destructive, doesn't care to get on the couch, crate trained (although she likes sleeping near the front door), walks nicely on a leash, and enjoys daily walks. During the day, when not napping, Runcie is patrolling the fence line protecting the property. She is a good watchdog and not timid about new situations.

Runcie will do well in a home with an all adult family with no kids, no cats, and no other dogs. She would be great as an only dog as she prefers your company and will need confident family leaders familiar with Pyr traits and behaviors. Please complete an Adoption Application if Runcie sounds like a perfect Pyr for you.

All dogs and puppies require VISIBLE fencing

Adoption Fee: $175. Northwest adopters pay the cost of transport to independent transport service ($225). Every GPRS dog is fully vetted (current on shots and has been spayed/neutered). Adoption applications can be found on our website at https://www.greatpyreeesrescuesociety.org .

ADOPTION, FOSTERING, AND DONATIONS are just some of the ways you can help a rescued dog. We have worked hard to cultivate a large network of volunteers to save this majestic breed. While monetary donations are always much appreciated, you can also help by donating your time as a GPRS foster or volunteer! 2/2/21 5:51 PM

animal.description:
Hi there, Im Indiana Bones! Or you can call me Bones or any other name you think fits a fine dog like me. Ill love whatever name you give me, because it means Im your dog. Ah, that sounds so nice. Ive been through a lot in my short life, but through it all, I prevail! Im smart and energetic and tons of fun. I approach everything in life with enthusiasm and excitement. And while I prefer a quiet, calm, low traffic home with just a few special people, once I settle in with you, I will make a truly wonderful companion.
Im a handsome, 2-year-old, 54-pound sweetheart with a happy, exuberant personality. And Im already housebroken too, although please be patient with me when we get home, because Ive been living in a shelter for quite a long time and its difficult to keep up a routine here. I came to Wayside last summer as a stray via animal control. I felt so alone and overwhelmed at the shelter. I was adopted for a while, but things didnt work out for me there. Although my family loved me very much and the feeling was mutual, they had a busy, hectic household and I just didnt fit in well with that environment. Thats ok though, because Im back at the shelter now and ready to meet my perfect match. I hope thats you!
During my time at Wayside, Ive been able to participate in lots of training classes. Ive worked so hard and Ive made excellent progress! Im one of the smartest dogs youll ever meet and I currently know cues for Sit, Stay, Down, Heel, Come, Place, and Mask. Ive learned all about loose leash walking. And I now understand how to greet people in an appropriate way with positive reinforcement. I love the focus and attention that comes along with my training and it gives me the chance to show off what a great dog I can be. My training partners describe me as incredibly intelligent, happy, fun, focused, and a quick learner. I do everything with gusto and Im eager to please. Id love to have a job to do. Please give me time to warm up and go at my own pace when we get home. If you gently praise and encourage me when Im a good boy and if you will provide me with consistency and patience, I will quickly learn what you expect from me. I want so much to make you happy!
I love to stay active and busy. Im an excellent running partner and a proud member of the Wayside Runners Club. I stay focused and keep a nice pace. I get so excited and happy to see my Wayside friends and Im always ready to walk or cuddle or just hang out. I go all in with whatever activity Im involved with, including playtime with my favorite toys. Im just a really nice friend to spend your day with. I need a home without kids or other animals. My Wayside friends are simply trying their best to set me up for a successful adoption and this sort of home will be best for me. Im looking for calm and quiet and a routine I can count on without the commotion that comes with a busy household. Im not the sort of dog who wants to go places and meet lots of new people. A calm homelife with you and daily exercise in a quiet area are all I want in life. Dog parks arent my thing, but a quiet hike in the woods with you sounds like heaven to me!
I hope youre as committed and dedicated to me as I will be to you. You see, I plan to love you unconditionally with every ounce of my being, once we are family. Life can be hard when youve never had stability or a family that will always be there for you. Thats what I want. Thats what I dream of. I want you to be my person and I want to be your dog.
Love, Indiana Bones
 ...
