You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Sizzling with puppy like spirit, two-year-old Snoopy is an endearing blend of affectionate and active. Fit, fine and funny (he has the sweetest snore) at 59 pounds, he adores attention, loves cuddling with his foster mom on the couch, rubbing his body up against hers and covering her face in kisses while she pet, pet, pets him. He also loves the resident children and is learning not to jump up in his eagerness to be with them. Curious, enthusiastic and energetic, he enjoys exploring every nook and cranny of his foster home, playing on his own with sturdy toys that he can throw around, chewing on Icelandic Lamb horns, and frisking about with his doggy foster friends. As much as he loves car rides, he tries to sit in his foster mom's lap and while he endures being bathed, he does try to get out of the tub! Motivated by toys, food and attention, he likes all treats and accepts them gently, knows "sit" and "off", is working on "stay", and although he's not yet leash or crate trained, he's fully housetrained. Now all Snoopy needs is a home with extremely affectionate adopters to complete his training, polish his manners and keep him mentally stimulated and physically satisfied fur-ever.

Animal Rescue of the Rockies believes that every pet should find a wonderful, caring home. To ensure each pet finds the best possible home, we ask that you fill out our Adoption Application so we can learn more about you and your household. We review each application we receive and will contact you within 48 hours. If your home sounds like a good match for you and the pet, the next step is to set up a "meet and greet." After meeting the pet, if you would like to proceed with adopting, we'll ask that you read and sign our Adoption Agreement and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fees help cover the costs of saving more lives! A home visit will be scheduled within one week of your new pet going home with you.

The adoption fee for this pet is $300. Our adoption fee covers the following:

- Spay/Neuter, Microchip

- DAPP vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for all DAPP boosters after adoption.

- Rabies vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for any rabies vaccinations after adoption.

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an adoption application by clicking here . We want our pets to go to a lifelong new home, so thank you for your patience during the adoption process!

Please email ARRColorado@gmail.com for more information, as we can not accept calls at this time. Our adoption process is:

1. Fill out our Adoption Application online. We'll contact you within 48 hours to answer any questions you may have about the pet.

2. If the pet looks like a great match, we'll schedule a meet and greet and ask you to fill out our online Adoption Agreement if you'd like to proceed with adopting. Once you've completed the Adoption Agreement and pay the pet's Adoption Fee, you can arrange to pick up your new furry family member!

The stray hold, at the Toccoa-Stephens County Humane Shelter, is 5 days. That allows owners a fair amount of time to come looking for their pets. On the sixth day, the animal becomes the property of the Toccoa-Stephens County Humane Shelter and is offered for adoption. An animal may be pre-adopted, however, if the owner comes forward, within the 5 day stray hold, the animal goes back to the owner. The adoption fee is refunded at that time.
TSCHS Adoption Procedure
Adoption Fees: Adoption fee includes spay or neuter, current (age appropriate) vaccinations, and a microchip.
Hours of Operation:
 Tues.-Saturday, 11-6

Pricing:
 Dogs $100 - Puppies $125
 Senior dogs $60

 Senior Cats $30

1747 Scenic Dr.
Toccoa, GA 30577
Phone: 706 282 3275
Fax: 706 886 7358
Email: Info@TSCHS.org

 Fill out an application
 Fill out a contract
 Pay the adoption fee
*Stray animals may be Pre-adopted before the stray hold is up. If an owner comes forward, the adoption fee is returned to the adopter. If the owner does not come forward, the animal is scheduled to be altered. When that is done, the pet can go home with the adopter.
Unfortunately, we are not able to hold animals without the adoption process being completed.
That includes the payment of the adoption fee. Adoptions are done on a first come, first served basis. Applications can be emailed and payment can be made via phone and at WWW.PayPal.me/TSCHS.

animal.description:
Meet beautiful, calm, and sweet Juliette!  She's a 10 year old mama that is now spayed and has a whole new lease on life!  She's about 60 pounds right now so she's right in between the medium and large range, and mostly black with a cute tuxedo white and black spotted patch down her chest.  She's been living out in rural North Carolina for the past 3 years while we've been trying to catch her and her various litters of puppies.  She had a laceration on her paw and we were finally able to bring her in and get her the medical attention and loving foster family she's long deserved!  We don't know anything about her story before she lived out in the wild, but she has impeccable house manners so we think she must have lived in a home before being abandoned and left to fend for herself.

She's both house and crate trained.  She's still learning the actual command "crate", but she's picking up quickly and will voluntarily walk in (with a treat leading the way of course), and then sit in there happily.  Most of all Juliette just wants to be around her people.  She's a lap dog at heart, and will sit quietly with you whether you're working from a home office or lounging on the couch watching tv.  She loves to be pet and rubbed and near you.  In fact she's so attached to people that to show her true heart and happiness we had to have a person next to her in most of her photos!  

If you're looking for a calm, quiet best friend then look no further!  However, if you're interested in a guard dog she is NOT your girl. She has little to no reaction to the doorbell or outdoor noises.  She's timid by nature but has no problem opening up quickly.  She's curious about cats but not aggressive.  Our cat was unsure and scared of her at first but is now used to her, so we like to say she's cat friendly on a cat-by-cat basis as long as they're introduced slowly.  Juliette gets along well with other dogs, but is mostly interested in being with her person.  

If Juliette is the right girl for you please apply here: https://www.surryanimalrescue.org/info/adoption

animal.description:
Max / Male / 5 Years / 14 lbs / Yorkie Mix / Maple, ON

Meet Max! Max was surrendered by his family when they could no longer care for him. Prior to being in foster care, Max had never known the comforts of being inside a home. He wants to be loved and is coming out of his shell every day in foster care. He will spin in a circle when he’s sees his people or gets to go outside for a walk! He loves to play with his toys and has become a master at fetch. His fosters describe him as a snuggly and affectionate velcro dog. They also say he has a huge personality and a face that will capture anyones heart. Max would do best with a patient and understanding family who is committed to helping him reach his full potential!

Once people have earned his trust - Max is truly a friend for life. He is the first to greet his family at the door and its all tail wags and kisses. With strangers, his space must be resected until he is comfortable. Generally if people try and enter his space before he is ready, or enter the home with high/unbalanced energy, he will growl or lunge. His trusted humans must be advocates for his space and instruct people to ignore him upon entering the home. If he is awarded the opportunity to come around on his own, he responds positively and will engage with them quickly. The high energy and unpredictable movements of children have made him uncomfortable, so he would likely prefer a child-free home.

Max has bonded closely with his foster family and isn’t a fan of when they leave. He may sit by the door and try and “block” it to encourage whoever is leaving to take him on the adventure. However, when he is left alone he will just sit and wait for their return. He is well mannered and has never clawed, whined or attempted to destroy anything. He is generally quiet in the home but does have a tendency to alert bark when someone knocks at the door.

Max is going for 3,15 minute walks a day around his neighbourhood, and could go more if the weather was nicer. If given adequate opportunities to use the washroom, he is fully potty trained. On leash he is generally well behaved and will walk beside his human. He can be startled by noises outside and may freeze to take in his surroundings. When he sees others dogs he may bark or lunge as a fear response to their presence. His fosters are currently working on desensitization to triggers by always having high value treats on hand. He has done well so far but this will need to continue in forever home!

Max is very smart and he figures out puzzles and games very quickly. He can learn a lot of tricks but you need to find the right treat that motivates him! He has already learned sit, twirl, come on the sofa, leave it, drop it, place, focus and wait. He has excellent impulse control. To continue building his confidence, Max will benefit from adopters committed to ongoing obedience and trick training. Max is sensitive to people touching his paws or being picked up, but is slowly getting used to it in the company of poeple he trusts.

Max’s ideal home would be in a detached home, with a fully fenced back yard. He loves to have the space to run and play. He doesn’t do well with stairs or hardwood so would prefer bungalows with a lot of carpeting in the home. He would do best outside of the city, and would thrive in quiet country or suburban life. He would love an active family who is looking for a hiking or walking companion. Max doesn’t like the company of other dogs or cats, so is looking to be the only pet in the home.

If you’re interested in adopting Max please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Max’s adoption fee is $750. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. Copy and paste the link to access the sign-up genius for an appointment: https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet for dogs and https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1 for cats.

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE:
http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Gunner was surrendered to a rural shelter when his owner died. He was part of a hoarding situation and is one of only 2 from the group that still needs rescue. He is good with people and other dogs, walks well on leash and has done well around loud and strange noises. Can you give him a forever home?

Adoption Coordinator: Homeward Trails Adoption Center
Location: Adoption Center
The adoption fee for this dog is $0. This fee INCLUDES spay/neuter and microchip.

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description: Teddy #7601 is a handsome 1-year-old male, Husky/Shepherd mix. Teddy is very friendly, affectionate, gentle and active. He is house trained. He knows the sit command. This active boy needs daily dedicated exercise and mental stimulation. A very tall fenced- in yard would be great; he is athletic and is a high jumper.  He seems to do well meeting other similarly sized dogs on walks. He enjoys long walks and is good on leash unless he gets into close proximity to something interesting, like a squirrel, then he pulls; we are working with him on this. He should NOT be in a home with cats.  He likes to be with his person and would do well with someone who is home a lot. As he tends to worry if he isn’t with his person, he should be crated when he is alone, at least initially. He rides well in the car.  He weighs 52 pounds and is full grown. This pup is microchipped. We believe you can always teach an ‘old’ dog new tricks, so we highly recommend continued obedience training for this smart pup; it stimulates the dog's mind and establishes a good dog/adopter relationship. This pup, like all pups, should be on heartworm preventative; an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure. If you are interested in adopting this dog, and are already approved to adopt through our organization, please contact dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with the pup’s name and ID number in the subject line. OTHERWISE, please submit an adoption application online: http://www.lastchanceanimalrescue.org/adoptus.html E-mail dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with questions. Stay tuned to our Facebook page for updates: www.facebook.com/LCARMD #adoptlove #PicMe #petsmartcharities

animal.description:
Location: Colonial Heights, VAMake some noise for our newest head....HONCHO!!!!

Ya'll.... let's just swoon over this handsome hunk for a minute!!!
Honcho is one of our newest running residents and my oh my is he a looker!!

Name: Honcho
Age: 10 months
Sex: Male
Breed: Pitbull with ** a mix of what we suspect may be Great Dane or another large breed*
**Please note-- his picture does not do his size any justice**
Weight: 65lbs and packing

What is Honcho looking for in a family?
One to call his very own (of course). He *will not* be fit for an apartment* This boy needs room to run (fenced in yard) or an *ACTIVE* owner dedicated to leash walking. Honcho knows basic commands but what he may not know sometimes is his size! He has legs for days and will use them full force for zoomies or for jumping up (we are working on that).

This hunk is treat and praise motivated and has also done well with his dog test. Although proper meet and greets will be required. Honcho forgets how large he is and can be pushy with other dogs.
He loves to play (toys, balls, chewies.. etc)
Honcho has been cat tested and is curious but mainly fearful.
He would do best in a home with older children (8 and over).

This boy is fabulous and we are looking for an equally fabulous home. If you think he would be a good fit and you Match his needs, please give us a call 804-520-9397.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Daisy is sweet and lovable and just LOVES attention. She does exhibit anxiety when left alone. Currently, she is in a foster home and is making sure to keep her foster dad in sight. We expect that Daisy will build her confidence in her foster home so that her anxiety will lessen. She likes to be with her human. Daisy prefers to sleep in her own bed on the floor (or with her human if allowed) but does NOT handle being crated. In her past, she has harmed herself in the crate.

She doesn't bother the resident cat--she is even submissive to her--until the cat hits the ground running. :) Daisy likes to give chase but not with intent to do harm.

Daisy is quiet once she is acclimated to the surroundings. She has whined/wimpered on her first day at her foster home but has settled down nicely. Daisy came from a house with children who she loved and who loved her.

We believe Daisy will thrive with another dog in the home.

She is currently not 100% housetrained but is being supported in her foster home--has had NO accidents during the night. In addition she is learning leash manners, but for now, we would recommend a fenced area. We will continue to update this profile as we learn more about Miss Daisy.

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Starsky! I came to the shelter when I was a wee baby. I was adopted and had a loving home but I guess I was too much for them. I am shy and timid around new strangers but I mean them no harm. I have never growled or shown my teeth, it just takes me a little longer to warm up to people. 

I don't like crates!!! I WILL destroy it to get out of it so my mom put me in training but I was only in it for about four weeks and had just started to make progress when they decided they just didn't have enough time and patience for a learning, growing puppy.  So here I am, looking for someone that has lots of love, patience and time to give me so I can be the bestest pupper I can be!!! I still can't be crated though, we will need to work on that. 

I have been around other dogs and seem to do okay. I don't really have much interest in them but they don't bother me. I have never been around cats but was in a home with older (11+ year) RESPECTFUL children! I love to lick kiddos faces!!! *SLURP* 

If you think you have the perfect home for me, please visit our website to submit an adoption application; www.whiteriverhumanesociety.org!!

I am an Black Mouth Cur mix, who is a very big boy. I enjoy playing with my siblings and the resident dogs in my foster home. I am inquisitive and like to explore all the things. So only older considerate kids for me, as I wouldn't want to accidently hurt anyone. My adoption fee is $550. Includes Travel fee, Health Certificate, vaccines, spay and microchip. animal.description:
Location: Arlington, VALilly is Looking For: Lilly is a young, energetic girl who will needs lots of play time and long walks! She'll also be happy to curl up with you at the end of the day, when she's all played out. She'll love obedience school so she can learn to be the best girl she can be.

What My Foster Says About Me:
Lilly is a spitfire and has a huge personality! Lilly loves to PLAY-- chasing and being chased is her absolute favorite. She's a huge clown and constantly makes me laugh, including when she's chasing her own tail and barking at herself in the mirror. Lilly is also an incredibly precocious, curious dog. She's always exploring her surroundings, you can practically see the wheels turning in her brain as she figures things out and experiences new things.

When she's done running out her energy at the park or on a long walk, Lilly is a little couch potato who likes to lounge and snuggle and wants to be close to her people.

Her other favorite hobby is watching birds outside and "protecting" us from them-- she's a very diligent "guard dog"! Lilly would love to go to a home with someone who is ready to help her channel her energy into long hikes or trips to the dog park, and to support her to learn basic obedience skills so that she can be the best dog she can be. She's a smart, spunky girl with lots of love to give!

Special Adoption Considerations: Lilly is a rambunctious teenager with lots of energy! Lilly gets anxious with strangers in the house so needs training to help her feel more secure. Because she can be anxious, she needs to go to a home with no kids under the age of 12.

More about Lilly: https://toolkit.rescuegroups.org/javascript/v2.0/template1?animalID=15666109&key=Mqr6gy1W

Contact: info@luckydoganimalrescue.org

Location: Arlington, VAI'm Looking For: Love and play time and more play time! This young girl is full of energy and ready to go, go, go wherever you go! She loves playing with other dogs and will need plenty of opportunities for that. She can be fearful of new people, so an apartment or condo where there are a lot of interactions may not be her best situation.

What My Foster Says About Me: Ellie May is doing well at our house and learning a lot from my very calm, confident dogs. She loves daycare and loves to play with other dogs; 2-3 days a week of daycare, or the equivalent, calms her down a lot! To be her best self, she needs to go to a calm, structured home with someone who can continue to work on her training and confidence building.

Special Adoption Considerations: Ellie May needs to go to a home with a second dog so she can work on her confidence. She also cannot go to a home with children under 12. - NO EXCEPTIONS!

More about Ellie May: https://toolkit.rescuegroups.org/javascript/v2.0/template1?animalID=14456003&key=Mqr6gy1W

Meet JellyBean! JellyBean is a super cute Jack Russell mix puppy looking for her forever home. She's around 5 months old and weighs about 16 pounds. She's probably going to stay small to maybe medium size. She has a super unique genetic makeup as she is short legged and long bodied but thick in the middle! 

JellyBean is super smart and eager to learn. She loves toys and treats and being a puppy! She's still mastering potty training, but she is a smart girl and will hopefully fully learn pretty quickly. She loves every dog she meets and would thrive if she had a fur-friend in her furever home. She also has met and loved some human kids and would likely enjoy having a non fursibling as well :) ! When it's time to calm down, she is happy to snuggle hard with her human and furry friends. 

JellyBean is spayed, up to date on vaccines and heartworm prevention, and microchipped. If you are interested in meeting JellyBean, please fill out the application at www.texassweetiesdogrescue.org. Her adoption fee is $250.

animal.description:
Howdy chums, it’s me, your friendly neighborhood Laith! I am a short, fat Redbone Coonhound mix, who weighs about 55 pounds and I'm about 6-7 years old. Dangit, I’m ready for my forever home. After living in the shelter and in a foster home forever, I declare that it’s high time for me to curl up on my forever couch and chew on some of those tasty forever bones and toys. 

I’ve come a heck of a long way from my shelter days. My foster mom’s been showing me all kinds of house dog stuff and I’m proud to say that I’m not only house trained, but I’ve got great inside manners. I don’t crate all that well but friend, you don’t even really need to crate me; I mostly like to curl up and sleep while you’re gone.

Now, I’ve gotta be honest- if you try and man handle me, I will be growly and grumpy (so please don’t pull me off your couch). However, if you got a treat and some kind words, I’ll do just about anything for you; all this simple hound needs is a little kindness and some bribery.

After living in a great foster home with fenced yards and other dogs, I’m confident that I’d do best in a home with a fenced yard and another dog. My favorite things in the world are car rides and playing with other dogs. So if you’re looking for a copilot to keep that passenger seat toasty, buddy, you’re looking at me!

Augusta Dog Adoptions is an all- volunteer, foster- based rescue. We take applications online and are scheduling individual adoptions in the Waynesboro, VA area during the pandemic.  A $175.00 adoption fee ($300 for puppies under 6 months old) helps us take care of all the dogs we rescue. All dogs are spayed/neutered, tested for heartworm and tick borne diseases (if old enough), microchipped, and vaccinated for rabies (if old enough), distemper/parvo and bordetella. They are also treated for internal and external parasites. Many dogs also receive extensive medical care such as dental work and major surgeries. For more information and to apply to adopt, please visit www.augustadogadoptions.org

animal.description:
Agnes is super sweet, smart, playful, cuddly, and adorable. She has amazing house manners (she doesn't have any hesitation for getting on furniture), takes treats appropriately, and loves pets.

Agnes appeared to be house-trained. She did not have any accidents in the house, and knew what was required during walks and outside breaks.

Agnes LOVED going for runs - tongue out, happy gallop. She LOVES toys and will chase a ball like crazy. She needs mental stimulation and a job. Training will benefit her, and she knows basic things like "sit" and "stay."

Agnes slept in the dead-center of my King sized bed, where she stretched out and snored loudly. She slept a good 9 hours before getting up and pawing at the door to be taken outside.

She was an excited car rider, but not anxious - liked getting into and out of the truck.

She is friendly with new people.  

Email adoption@wilco.org to meet her.

Rigby von Rathenow is a very handsome 2 year old Shepherd mix. Handsome and happy, Rigby is always ready for his next adventure. Rigby is ready for his forever home and maybe it’s with you!

animal.description:
Location: Arlington, VAHi! I'm Annabelle, and there's nothing I love more in the world than giving kisses to my favorite humans! One piece of cheese (call it a bribe if you want) and I will consider us BEST FRIENDS.

Here are a few things I like a lot:
- naps
- chilling on the couch
- soft toys
- tug of war
- squirrels
- hiking
- snacks

I'm super low-maintenance at home. Got work to do? Cool, I'll just squeeze in a quick nap! Wanna chill on the couch with me? That's perfect! Got a treat to share? Check out my skills -- I can sit, lie down, and give you my paw to earn it. I don't mind my crate and I sleep quietly all night.

Do you like to hike? I'd love to be your hiking buddy! My foster mom took me on a long hike and I spent all 7 miles grinning from ear to ear. I also love walks around the neighborhood!

I can't wait to find my forever home! I'd like to end up in a single family house so there are limited scary noises around!

What My Foster Says About Me: Annabelle is a very sweet dog! She is housetrained and loves car rides. She has not damaged anything since living with her foster family. Annabelle still sleeps in the crate and spends some time during the day there too.

Annabelle is very low-key at home and loves snuggles, giving kisses, and getting all the attention! She is super gentle with her human foster siblings and immediately bonded with her human foster brother when he came home from college. At home, Annabelle often approaches members of her foster family with her rope to play tug of war. She does try to take any opportunity to get on the couch or bed but who doesn't like being cozy?

Annabelle is very smart and trainable - she knows how to sit, give you a paw, lay down and will do everything at once for a treat! She loves to play with different little blankets or other pieces of fabric! She also loves to chase balls, play tug of war with ropes and she loves to run. She gets 1-2 daily walks and does well on the leash - her foster dad will often jog with her because she loves to run next to him - if someone is looking for a dog as a running partner, Annabelle would be good for that. She also loves hiking!

Annabelle can be a bit unsettled by strangers in the home, but with a slow and proper introduction she will be a visitor's best friend in no time! Because she can be a little shy and has exhibited resources guarding tendencies, we would like Annabelle to be the only dog in her home.

Annabelle is a very sweet girl who LOVES her humans and will thrive in a home with an experienced dog owner who is dedicated to helping her be the best pup she can be!

Lucky Dog cannot guarantee any dog is housebroken. All of our dogs are working on their crate training.

Learn more about Annabelle: https://toolkit.rescuegroups.org/javascript/v2.0/template1?animalID=15947613&key=Mqr6gy1W

Contact: info@luckydoganimalrescue.org

animal.description:
Handsome and sweet-natured Raja has been soaking up some TLC in one of our experienced foster homes. He is now super ready for adoption to his forever home!

Raja gets along with everyone. He has lived with big and small dogs, cats, children, and adults, and his gentle demeanor never changes. As his foster home says, “He is completely house trained and is one of the most well-mannered dogs possible. We have yet to hear him bark and he seems to know exactly what you want at all times.”  

Raja loves being outside, so a fenced yard would be helpful. Age has stiffened his movements, so long term, limited to no stairs is very helpful. He is on medications to help his mobility, and those medications must continue. 

A beautiful hound mix, Raja thrives with a comfortable spot to rest his head, a chance to lay quietly in the sun, and the companionship of humans who love him. He will give back tenfold on the love, guaranteed!

Is this you? Please fill out an adoption application and we will be glad to answer any questions! WE WILL ONLY ANSWER QUESTIONS ONCE AN ADOPTION APPLICATION IS FILED ON OUR WEBSITE, topdogfoundation.org. Thank you for respecting this.

animal.description:
Kiki is a husky/German Shepherd mix who was born on 1/17/2019. She’s very energetic and loves spending time outdoors, but she loves to cuddle at night after a long day of running around. She’s a little nervous around other dogs, but with a proper introduction, she does just fine! Kiki is full grown at 53 lbs. She would do best in a home with older children as she’s still a little timid. She’s house broken and working on kennel training. Kiki is heartworm negative, up to date to vaccines and scheduled to be spayed on February 17. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
GOOD with dogs, GOOD with kids, GOOD with cats

ADOPTION FEE: $400 www.unbreakabull.com/adopt

Hi everyone!!!! My name is Rex, and I am 1 year old and just the goofiest thing ever! I came to the shelter when my previous owner passed away and there was no one to take care of me. I came very scared and shy of everything, but since coming to rescue and getting settled, I am doing so much better and am starting to let my personality shine. While I am one year old, I am still learning so many things. My foster mom says that I am so sweet and so respectful. I am also learning to play with my foster fur brother and that is fun. I really like dogs, and I hope to have a playmate in my forever home, but I would also be quite content being the sole dog. I am working on confidence building as well. There are things that will startle me, like tennis balls, but that’s just because they are new items to me. Once I discover that they aren’t scary, I am totally okay with them. I am curious of the cat that lives here, but I am super good when redirected to leave it alone. We are learning to co-exist in the same space. I am also learning to be good in my kennel. I do okay for the most part, but I am working on it. I only bark when I have to go outside to go potty, so I pretty much have the hang of that. All that I am looking for in life is someone who can teach me the ropes of being a model fur-citizen, give me tons of love and attention, and the comfiest place to sleep. If you think that you are ready to be my person forever, please fill out my application, and let’s make this adventure final! Until then, I’m going to do some more investigating of this tennis ball thing and see what the hype is all about when it comes to it and my fur-foster brother. Until we meet, Rex (UPDATED 01/21/21)

The name is Binx. I am a youthful, energetic young lass, who would love nothing more than to be your adventure companion. I haven't been with MaxFund for very long, but I'm ready to explore the world! I love humans, and am always on my best behavior with them.
 But I don't do so great with other dogs. We are working on proper introductions with other dogs, but it will be a slow process. For now, I would do best in a household with no other dogs. 

Are you ready to be my adventure time companion? Call MaxFund at 303-595-4917 to set up an appointment for me to meet you!

MaxFund is a physical shelter located at 1005 Galapago St in Denver, Colorado.
If you are interested in learning more about a dog, please call 303-595-4917 to make an appointment to meet a dog.
.
This PetFinder account is managed by volunteers, and the most up-to-date information is at the shelter.
How our adoption process works:
1. You MUST come into the shelter to meet a dog you are interested in (and meet a few others, while you’re at it!)
                 Our hours are 10-5 Mon, Wed, Thu Fri / 11-5 Saturday / 12-5 Sunday
                We suggest you call ahead to be sure the dog(s) do not have pending applications
2. You will fill out your adoption application, including references, after finding a dog you’d like to adopt
3. The application review and reference checks will take up to 3-5 business days; you will not be able to bring a dog home same-day
                We only take 2 applications per dog, before they are unavailable. This is why we suggest you call ahead to check the status of the pup!
 
We do not adopt out-of-state.
Thank you for choosing to rescue!

animal.description:
Bonnie has a very loving personality. She is smart, intuitive, playful and a little silly at times. She is fully housebroken and knows how to sit, lay down, and roll over. While she doesn't like going in the crate, she will remain calm once inside. Bonnie's foster mom reports that she is very respectful of household properties such as beds, couches and even trash; she won't touch it unless you give her permission. Bonnie is very excited to meet new people and is working on learning not to jump on them. When she wants attention that she's not getting, she will come up to you and put her toes on yours, and nudge your knees with her nose as if to say "come on, you know you want to play". If you don't have time (or don't want to play), Bonnie will leave you alone if you ignore her. Bonnie can be a bit picky about food; she prefers her dry food to be completely mixed with the wet food. Otherwise, she won't eat. Bonnie's favorite activities are going on walks and playing catch & tug of war, people watching and sleeping. Her least favorite thing in the world is a cat. If you are interested in meeting sweet Bonnie, you can submit an appointment request here: 

https://forms.office.com/Pages/ResponsePage.aspx?id=lsJ_8Hpq8k2OaDbCdJiGnZ0KUdNlMOxGs9o3MWhive1UOFRNUUhQMlFUSlM4UU04RUdEQ1dQNUFWTC4u

Current weight: 70 pounds
Current age: 2 years old

animal.description:
Meet Prince Florian (aka Prince)! Prince is young, roughly a year and half. He came to us late last year with the rest of what we, at the rescue, called the Disney family. Along with him, his lady Snow White and their seven puppies were confiscated from a very bad situation and brought to us for rescue. 

Puppies are now weaned and vetted and all in their forever homes. Momma Snow White found her forever home and is living her best life, that just leaves Prince Charming left to find his happy ending! 

Prince is filly vetted and neutered and ready to go home! Prince loves all people is a happy, silly, playful boy! He  loves his toys and does a good job not chewing them up. Cardboard on the other hand is villainous and will be destroyed by the brave Prince. 

Prince is a quiet dog and goes great in his kennel. He seems to be house broken and dog selective. He prefers female dogs and will require a meet and greet before adoption. Prince cannot be around cats! He does have a strong prey drive. 

Will you be Prince Charming’s happy ever after!?

** Special Placement **

As you can see, Lucy is a real cutie! She is about 3 years old, 34 pounds, and appears to be a Spaniel/Aussie mix. Lucy is a lively, active girl who is house trained, and loves to ride in the car. She is completely devoted to her person, currently her foster mom.

Lucy is slow to accept new people and will snap at them if they persist in trying to make friends. She will come around, especially if treats are involved, but she needs to make friends on her own terms.

Lucy gets along with other dogs but would prefer to be an only dog so she gets all the attention. She is good with dog savvy cats. Lucy requires a home with no children and one that does not have many visitors. If you are interested in adopting Lucy, please go to our website to read the details:

S.P.C.A. Albrecht Center For Animal Welfare
 Requirements for Adoption
1. Most of our dogs will require a fenced in yard to allow them to play safely outdoors.
2. If you have other pets in the home, you will need to provide proof of current rabies vaccines.
3. If you rent your home, we will need to verify that you have your landlord’s approval for the pet.
4. If you have other pets, we strongly encourage you to bring them to the shelter to meet the animal you wish to adopt first, to make sure everyone will get along.
The S.P.C.A. Albrecht Center for Animale Welfare adoption fees vary. Please call the shelter for each pet's adoption fee. 803-648-6863. Adoption fees include age-appropriate vaccinations, deworming, spay/neuter and microchip implantation and registration. Heartworm testing and treatment is also included for adult dogs. love

animal.description:
This sweet little old lady is Lola, and she is absolutely darling. Her favorite thing in the world is to be with her people, and she loves all of the petting, lap time and snuggles she can get??. She also loves anything soft and can often be found rooting around in her blankets and bedding to make the perfect nest. 

Lola currently lives in a foster home with 2 big dogs and can often be found snuggled up next to one of them for warmth if her people aren’t available. She hasn’t done as well with small dogs and cats, but bigger mellow dogs that don’t challenge her have been fine. She has also done well with a toddler and would do fine with respectful children. 

Lola is 12 years old and is still spunky and vibrant for a senior. She is pretty much house trained but does have the occasional accident. Due to the anatomy of her respiratory system she can sound snorty and congested, and is more prone to upper respiratory infections. Her future family will need to keep an eye on her and if she sounds extra congested or her discharge is not clear she will need to get in to see a vet and will likely need a course of antibiotics. 

We are partnering with the Animal Welfare Society in Kennebunk Maine to find Lola some new digs. She is amazing and will make some very lucky adopter very happy!!!


PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior pets have a history of being kept up to date on vaccines, annual exams and recommended bloodwork. We also do home checks to make sure that your home environment meets the needs of the particular dog you are interested in.

If you’re interested in adoption, please fill out our online adoption survey at https://www.olddogsnewdigs.com/adoption-survey/

animal.description:
"How yoose doing? I'm Hurb and I just joined the adoptable doggy crew at Providence Animal Center from ACCT, so I'm an #ACCTtoPAC rescue! 

I'm around 9 years young, a solid 67 pounds, and I'm all set to move right into your heart & home today - already neutered, microchipped & up to date on vaccinations. 

I'm a staff and volunteer favorite. Don't let my age fool you! I love going on walks and I have a playful disposition. The folks here describe me as affectionate, independent, fearless, quiet, and smart. I have been taking on the role of official office dog. My jobs include making sure the staff are providing me with plenty of attention and hugs. They were slacking on a comfy bed, so I let them know that was a must for important office dogs.

If you are looking for well mannered gentleman, then look no further! I am housebroken, incredibly sweet, and I will make sure to keep our days together are fun and interesting. I do need to disclose that some of elder ailments such as cataracts which impair my vision, but I am still able to see light and motion and I am deaf, but these things don't hold me back from living my best live with the right doggy roommate. With my sweet disposition, the staff also think I'd likely be a great roommate for kids of any age!

On a recent sleepover with one of PAC's loving foster moms, I was told to pass along that I'm "a wonderful house guest, so gentle and loving." I'm totally enjoying hanging out with her and her dog pals in their warm, comfy home!

The staff would love to match you with your new best friend forever - and hopefully that's me! If you are interested in meeting me in person, please schedule an appointment here: ProvidenceAC.org/AdoptADog. My paws are crossed I will see you very soon! XOXO-Hurb

P.S. Someone is so excited for me to find my fur-ever home, that they have sponsored my adoption fee! That means I can join your family today for FREE! Woohoo!!"

-------
During your appointment, you will be able to meet a selection of pets in the Kennels or Cattery that day. New pets are arriving daily!
-------

Providence Animal Center relies on adoption fees and donations to save pets! Adoption fees vary per pet. To find out this pet’s adoption fee or for more information, please call the Adoption Center with this pet’s ID number.

Can’t adopt? Consider fostering or donating! Visit https://providenceac.org/support-us/ for more information on how you can support the lifesaving mission!

"Hi, there!  Thank you for stopping by to read about me!  I'm Kristoff and I recently joined the adoptable doggy crew at Providence Animal Center's lifesaving facility.  

I'm just over 1 year old and about 61 pounds.  I'm all set to join my new family - already neutered, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations.  

I spent some time with a foster family and they called me a "lovebug". I'm not 100% sure why they called me a bug because I'm a dog... but I think it means I am very affectionate and just want to make you smile. My foster family says I'm a good walker and I'm learning how to do all the grown up dog things like sit and go to the bathroom outside. If you have another dog in the house for me to play with, that would be SO much fun because I love to play with other dogs! 

The staff think my ideal home would would have another doggy roommate. I love to play! No cats please. I'm a little too interested in them. If your family has children, the staff think that older children that are high school aged or older would be best. I can be rambunctious! 

I am lucky enough to be staying with one of PAC's fabulous foster partners, Perfect Pooch in King of Prussia, while I wait for my forever family to find me.  If you are interested in more information about me including my most up-to-date status and/or would like to set up a meeting with me, please contact the fabulous staff at Perfect Pooch today at 610-337-7698! We hope to hear from you soon! XOXO Kristoff"

-------
During your appointment, you will be able to meet a selection of pets in the Kennels or Cattery that day. New pets are arriving daily!
-------

Providence Animal Center relies on adoption fees and donations to save pets! Adoption fees vary per pet. To find out this pet’s adoption fee or for more information, please call the Adoption Center with this pet’s ID number.

Can’t adopt? Consider fostering or donating! Visit https://providenceac.org/support-us/ for more information on how you can support the lifesaving mission!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Jenny Cope (giveadogahome@live.com) for more information about this pet.

Be sure to read ALL information provided.

A PET IS FOR LIFE -
THINK ABOUT THE INVESTMENT!

JERRY was saved from a high kill shelter in Texas where dogs often have only 3 days to be saved. JERRY is neutered rabies, core vaccines, heartworm/tick disease tested negative for all. He is de-wormed, monthly preventatives and microchipped. At the time of rescue in the middle of January 2021, he weighed around 50.00 pounds and has an estimated date of birth 3 November 2017

. We cannot say for sure what breed he is, so we expect families to do their own research on his look and size and decide what breed you think she is and if you have the lifestyle suitable for his needs.

When JERRY arrived at the rescue in Sebec, Maine on 15th January 2021 he was very shy and fearful. When in his kennel he would give a warning growl, letting me know he was unsure and uncomfortable at which I respected and left him alone for a while so that he could get settled. I found that when Jerry feels he is cornered he will let you know by growling and when I back off and get to his level he gets more relaxed and will come up to smell and get his ears scratched. When cleaning his kennel I would make sure he was inside before I cleaned outside as this is where he felt the most threatened and trapped. After a few days he and his kennel neighbour had gotten into each others kennel and were sharing the elevated dog bed and his demeanor instantly changed, him obviously gaining confidence through the happy-go-lucky Sophie.

After a few days Sophie was adopted and Jerry had to get used to being in the kennel on his own, his affection for me was great, there was no more fear and he was becoming very attached. Jerry had a meet and great with a GSD experienced family, but when I took him out to meet them, he again became very fearful and only wanted to be near me. After a few minutes we decided that putting him back in the kennel and spending time with him through the gate might help, however, it just seemed to escalate his fear and his fearful growling, turned into barking and we both agreed that he was not ready for his new home yet - more so with the family having a small child and not being able to dedicate and commit to the training and work he will need.

Instead of going back in a kennel, I put Jerry in with the remaining dogs that had been relocated to the communal area in the kennels where there is access to a large, secure fenced in area. At first very cautious and wary, which was to be expected as several younger dogs all wanting to jump on him, however, after a while he settled down, but lay at the gate waiting for me. After a few hours he did great and we all went outside and he got to explore the outside and the snow - he was very happy and loved being able to run and seemed settled now with the other dogs. I did, however, end up moving him again to a kennel over in the shop area, as I didn't feel comfortable leaving him unsupervised with the other younger dogs jumping on him all the time. If we don't find him a forever home soon, I do intend to bring him up to the house where he will be with many other dogs, but older and not wanting to jump on him.

Jerry is a very sweet, affectionate boy who has clearly had something happen to him where he has lost trust, it could be something as simple as his family dumping him in a shelter, shepherds get very attached to their people and it shatters their hearts when they dump them. He might have been caught as a stray and a catch pole or something used that scared him, or we could assume many other scenarios, but the truth is we do not know. We just want to find the absolute perfect family to give this boy what he needs to build and gain trust and be the happy, confident boy that he should be.

We are looking for a family that is active for sure, someone that understands the need of not just physical exercise but training and lifetime mental stimulation. He is going to need a family that is able to give him space where he can decompress and learn to trust his family and understands that this can take time.

More pictures and possible video's can be found on his page on the rescue website.

We do not know how Jerry is with cats or livestock, but expect families to be prepared to work through any potential issues and ensure a safe and happy living environment for all.

All dogs use dog doors to go out and do their business or to enjoy the cool, fresh weather in their dog runs or communal areas. We cannot say if a dog is house-trained, however, we expect families to understand that all dogs need a transition period and accidents could happen and training is most definitely needed.

You MUST understand that dogs need time to decompress and adapt to their new environment and home. It is a HUGE transition they make from the kill shelter, being vetted, on transport for 3 days and arriving in Maine where the temperature and such is very different to what they have only known. In rescue there is what is known as the "3 Point Rule" Days 1-3 your dog is stressed, anxious, confused as to where they are now. Weeks 1-3 your dog is adjusting, settling in, learning things. At the 3 month point, your dog understands they are home, and have built up a trusting relationship where they feel loved and secure.

All dogs are fed Rachael Ray Nutrish PEAK Natural Dry Dog Food, Grain Free Western Grasslands Recipe with Bison. Rachael Ray Nutrish Peak Dog Food receives the Dog Food Advisor's second-highest tier rating of 4.5 stars.

JERRY is available for adoption for an adoption fee of $550

This fee is not negotiable and is used to cover the rescue costs of pulling, vetting, health certificate, transport from Texas to Maine, monthly preventatives, supplements, food, general day to day cost of running a brick and mortar rescue and anything else that is needed. Canadian adopters need to know that customs charge 15% taxes when entering into Canada.

Due to borders being closed, it is up to families to call the US and Canadian borders to find the current details on border crossing. Animal Welfare is deemed essential in the US, but quarantine rules entering back into Canada must be followed.

If you feel that you have the heart and home to give this precious soul a wonderful life, please go to our website, under the ADOPTION INFO tab, complete, then submit the APPLICATION. Our process takes around 1-2 days, and ensuring your references are aware that we will be calling, could speed up the process. Once you have been approved, we discuss any questions in regards to the dog you are wanting to adopt, then you complete and submit the contract, make payment and then we can work out the pick up / transport arrangements.

Please do NOT submit an application if you are not looking to take home a new best friend within the next few weeks.

https://www.giveadogahome-sanantonio.org/forms/form?formid=5838

ALL Dogs are LOCATED AT THE RESCUE IN SEBEC, MAINE. We post in various states along the east coast and Canada where we have had lots of successful adoptions to enable more exposure for these beautiful saved souls. Families will need to be prepared to travel to the rescue to meet and take home their new best friend. Sebec is located just outside the towns of Dover-Foxcroft and Milo (approx 8 miles) and approx 45 miles from Bangor. There are also lots of hotels, motels, pet friendly accommodations and wonderful camp-sites for the more adventurous families and what a great way to get to know your new best friend.

Click here to watch a video of JERRY.

Willow is a community post for Animal aid Society in Hampton – www.animalaidsociety.org

Willow is a very sweet, smart and independent girl. She knows a handful of basic cues, loves hanging out curled up in the doggie bed with her favorite stuffy and on occasion, she’ll even engage in a game of fetch. Her favorite thing to do is sniff sniff sniff!

Willow is a behavioral special needs dog as she is very protective of her toys and food. We recently learned she may have a food allergy and has had multiple ear infections, so she has a sensitivity to things around her head including a collar and harness. Once the relationship and trust is built Willow is very attached to her person and will always be right by your side.

Willow needs a patient, devoted person who will earn his trust, and respect his boundaries.

Animal Aid will provide free sessions with Willow’s certified professional trainer to help that special person learn how to help this special dog.

Potential adopter must have a securely fenced yard, and live in an adult-only household.

If interested in meeting Willow, please contact our Training Coordinator at training@animalaidsociety.org

* Will consider interested applications outside of a 45 mile radius of the shelter.

animal.description:
This little cutie is Colt.  He is a Border Collie mix, maybe with lab. We are not exactly sure what his DNA says, but we know he is a super cute, friendly puppy ready to find his forever home.  At around 16 lbs now, we think Colt will be in the range of 50-60 lbs when full grown.

Born in early November 2020, Colt is happy, loves food, playtime and people!! He is smart, loving and easy going.  He will need great socialization to help him grow into a well-mannered adult dog. Colt is a lower key guy who still wants to go for walks with his people and see the world, but he wouldn't be a great fit for a family interested in a running partner. Colt wants opportunities to learn through obedience classes and mental engagement (trick training, games, puzzles).

Colt can be an only dog in his forever home.  He would not mind a friendly canine sibling to model great behavior and play with.  Because of his sharp puppy teeth, homes with older kids will be considered. For his safety, we will also prefer homes with physically fenced yards: he is too young for invisible fencing.

Families that work outside the home need to include information in their application about how they will accommodate potty training because Colt may not be left home alone for more than a few hours a day. 

Colt is located in the Minneapolis, MN area. If you think you're a good fit for him, please fill out an application at hoabcr.org/how-to-adopt 

As a foster-based rescue, we do not have a central facility to visit. Meet and greets with specific dogs are arranged once your adoption application (not an inquiry email through Petfinder) has been received, processed, and approved. We are located in Minnesota and adopt to an area 400 miles from Minneapolis/St. Paul.

The adoption fee for puppies is $400 + MN sales tax. This fee includes spay or neuter at the age of 5 months at one of our veterinary clinics. Puppies are up to date on vaccinations at the time of adoption.

animal.description:
Bailey is a sweet, loving, silly, submissive girl. She had a rough start and is shy, but she has blossomed into a playful girl that loves to have fun or snuggle. She enjoys playing with other dogs, snuggling with cats, snuggling with her humans, playing with her people and other dogs, chasing toys and tennis balls, walks, and enjoying her fenced-in yard. She is very food motivated (even veggies, kibble), so that is a big help with training. She is also play-motivated. She would adore a home with another dog for her to play with, and she plays with her foster sibling, who is a fraction of her size, safely (it provides her foster parents plenty of entertainment and laughs). In fact, by being gentle, non-threatening, and persistent, she is the first dog to ever get her foster sister to play! She knows sit (hand signal, verbal), off, has a great recall in the backyard, and is a treat-catching star (very entertaining)! She enjoys sleeping in her crate or with her humans and is mostly potty trained. While we’re unsure of her history, she’s wary of people hovering over her, and she’s very sensitive to human body language, so that can be used to her new family’s advantage to help her feel more comfortable. Bailey has worked so hard and overcome so much to trust humans, and she deserves a wonderful forever home with humans who love her.  She's about 2 years old and 20 lbs.
Bailey would do best with:
·       No younger children. Any older children should be patient and gentle.
·       Minimal car rides, at least for now. She gets car sick.
·       Another dog to play with
Adoption fee $400

All UnderDogs are spayed/neutered, heartworm checked, microchipped, up to date on vaccines and heartworm/flea/tick preventatives.  For consideration for one or more dogs, we require that an on-line application is filled out.  

TO ADOPT THIS DOG PLEASE FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AT https://underdogrescueofflorida.com/. 

Sorry, we do not adopt outside of Florida.  Applicants are subject to a home visit, and veterinary references will be checked. Please include a vet reference (including phone number) when applying online.

Our application process:
FIRST, an application must be approved for adoption from our rescue.
SECOND, we determine whether the dog that has been applied for is a "good match" for the household that wants to adopt him/her.  We take into consideration the dog's activity level, compatibility with other members of the household (human and other pets), etc.
If your application has been approved, but the dog you applied for is no longer available, please take the time and look over our adoptable dogs again.  We will make every effort to find the right dog for an approved applicant.

We hope you agree and understand that our goal to find the best forever home is our #1 priority! Please fill out an Adoption Application at https://underdogrescueofflorida.com/

animal.description:
Bishop is a handsome Red Nose Pit Bull. Bishop came to us from a family that unfortunately did not have enough time for him. He has spent a lot of time in a kennel and will need some training. He is a very sweet boy, and loves to play. He needs someone that will have time to run with him and play.  He dearly wants a home that will be his forever home. 

Bishop is 8 months old. His current weight is around 50/55 pounds. He will be neutered and up to date on shots. 

His fee is $150.00. The adoption fee includes the initial vaccines, spay/neuter surgery, microchipping and a deworming. 

We are currently only open by appointment. Due to the recent pandemic, we are looking at the safety of our workers/volunteers that are there to take care of the animals. Only serious inquiries will be considered.

Please visit our website to fill out an application so we can better assist you in your search for your next fur baby.  http://www.achs-pets.com/Application.html 

We are a BEST MATCH facility. We try to match the pet’s personality and needs with the family’s needs and lifestyle to increase the likelihood of a lifetime happy relationship for the whole family. The online application we provide on our website, achs-pets.com, is a preliminary application. After you have completed the application, please give us 3 to 5 business days to process it. We check vaccine records for current & past pets as well as Landlord approval if you do not own your home. We hope you will understand our effort to provide our animals with the best new situation that is possible.

animal.description:
Meet Beanie! This sweet little nugget was abandoned in a dog park, tied to a fence. She was out there for most of the day as passers-by noticed her but assumed someone was coming back for her. Finally, at dusk, a Good Samaritan realized no one was coming and contacted Animal Control for help. Unfortunately, the local shelter is experiencing a Covid outbreak, and its employees are minimal, so there was no plan to help her. The Good Samaritan took her in and contacted Worthy Dog for help. We took her to the vet right away and confirmed she's a young, healthy pup who just needs a better family.

Beanie has been fostered with both small and large dog, and does well with both. She loves to play, wrestle, and run zoomies with her dog buddies. She's a fast pup, too, and needs to be watched around open doors at first. She doesn't necessarily want to flee, but she may take the chance to explore until she learns the rules of your home. Her foster mom has used the crate when there's a lot of in and out activity. Beanie will bark for a very short time, and settle down and lay there quietly until let out.

Beanie has proven herself to be a confident, active, feisty, spunky, sassy, vocal, and sweet loving puppy. She is everything that goes with a puppy. She is bright, inquisitive, and learns quickly. She is mouthy and wants to play by nipping at things - she may nip at your ankles, shoes, etc. She is still learning manners and needs some basic correction with a water bottle and a firm "no" to learn this is not appropriate behavior. Like all young pups, she needs a commitment to daily exercise, playtime, and lots of chew toys to entertain her.

As far as her people skills, she is a very affectionate pup who loves to sit on your lap and cuddle. She's crate trained, sleeps well through the night, and will put herself to bed when she's tired. She's mostly house trained and had a couple of potty incidents the first few days in her foster home, but nothing since. She knows to "go potty" outside and does her business in pretty short order when you take her out. She is not food aggressive, and is generally well-mannered and gentle when she takes treats.

Beanie is getting daily walks with the rest of her pack and loves to go outside. She may pull a little but quickly figures out the pace and adjusts. She tends to bark at new people at first but will settle down. She's too vocal for a condo dog and would benefit from another social, playful pup in her home to learn from. While she's not being fostered with kids, we think she would be fine with older kids who understand she's mouthy and not biting to be mean. She's been around the neighbor kids (9 and 13 years old), and Beanie loved them. She doesn't mind being picked up and carried and has made friends with the neighborhood dogs, so she is social by nature.

Beanie is a charming, fun pup with adorable big ears. She's going to make some lucky family very happy and just needs adopters who are ready to work through puppy mode.

No Condos
Best paired with another young playful pup

animal.description:
Meet our shepherd girls, Gris and her "mom" Freddi. They are a bonded pair and we do wish that they stayed together. These 2 sweet girls came from a less than wonderful background where routine healthcare was lacking. Both girls will be spayed on February 4th. Fredrica, black and tan, is approximately 8 years old. She has ear and skin issues. She is missing patches of hair due to fleas, but with proper medical treatment, she is feeling better and fur is growing back. Her daughter, Gris is approximately 4 years old. She too had ear issues at some point, but it appears to have cleared up. Gris and Freddi are very in tune to each other. One is always seeking out the other. They do not crave human attention, but maybe they haven't really received KIND human attention, until now. They are tolerant and pleasant girls. VERY playful They love chasing each other in the big yard, stealing toys from each other like there is only 1 toy in the yard! Watching them run free and happy is great! If you have room in your home and heart for these girls, please send your application soon!  


Perry County Animal Rescue (PCoAR) 717-589-3005 Millerstown, PA www.perrycountyanimalrescue.org

The girls met Ned the rescue cat. Ned said they are fine. Girl had no interest ion him what so ever. He was insulted but got over it. He would be willing to hang out with them. We agree. The girls seem fine with cats.

animal.description:
TUCKER!  

This little fella lives to love, snuggle and hug.   He is 20 pounds of personality plus!  Tucker is ready to join a home where he is the center of attention, the apple of someone’s eye, co-pilot, lap warmer, walking companion and couch snuggler.  

Tucker is sweet, smart and about 2 years old.  His current foster mom has been enjoying getting to know him and his joy for life.  He is awesome in the car, good leash skills and loves his walks around the hood and on trails.  He has learned the doggie door and has access to the outdoors and is house-broken.  He has good manners in the home. 

Tucker is the guy who wants to have a full time job being your best friend and he can adapt to many situations which makes him perfect for joining his family on outings, going to work, helping with errands, etc..    Tucker is not the guy who will be happy being left alone.  He really wants to be that special someone in your life.  He is a loving, playful and active fella that will enjoy a similar human mom and/or dad.

He does live with another small dog in his foster home and did well with other dogs at the shelter, however we are looking for a home without any dogs as he would prefer to have a lap all to himself.   
Tucker is also learning basic skills such as sit and stay and does stay in the crate at night, but would be in heaven to be able to snuggle in bed with his person/people. 

This boy is ready to bring some serious love and friendship into a home. We are looking for the home that yearns for that canine companionship that a dog like Tucker can bring.  
 
Tucker is being fostered in Essex Junction, VT.    We’re looking for a family with no other dogs, dog savvy kitties okay,  children over 10, and home more often than not. 

Apply here:  http://longtraildogs.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
CAMO rescued Joey in early January. His foster can hardly believe the transformation since then! From completely shutdown to confident companion, our little guy is now ready to live his best life in his perfect forever home. 

Joey is a 16lb Yorkie/ Silky Terrier  (Aprox) eight years old being fostered in the DFW area. He’s completely blind but that doesn’t stop him from loving life! Joey has fit right in with his foster’s own dogs who range from young to geriatric, from less than five pounds to over 120 pounds. He also doesn’t mind the cats and happily follows his foster mom around the house, often curling up on a rug or cushion wherever she might be.

Sweet Joey is crate and house trained. He goes outside in a courtyard to potty and follows the sound to come when called. He’s a quiet boy and not a barker. His perfect person is someone who is home most of the time and will have patience while he learns his way around his new home. Joey lifts his body to be picked up and loves to be petted and cuddled. He also really, really loves treats!

Want to meet this special little dude? To apply, go to https://www.camorescue.com/adoption-application.

animal.description:
Hubert here. I was surrendered to the rescue as I became way too much for my person to handle. I decided I did not like the neighbor's dogs and this became a big issue for us all. That being said, I DID live with a small female dog and a cat. I was not the nicest to the cat and wasn't interested in sharing food with her. So cats will be a MAYBE. I would never hurt, but I am a big boy and I may hurt in my play. I am a bit of a drooler and won't mind having my face wiped or my paws when I come in from outside. I will bring my leash when you ask me to or I'm ready to go out for potty. I will crate if I have to. I love my toys and play time. I will sit proper like a gentleman and know other simple manners too. I will clean up after you, if you leave socks or underwear lying around. But I just might eat them! I'm looking for an easygoing life. A couch potato with some snuggles sound good to me! I will need an owner who can handle a big boy like myself. Someone who can be firm. I do have a guarding instinct that is part of my breed, but I am a love bug too. I am hoping for an owner who has experience with my breed. If that's you, send an application soon! 


Perry County Animal Rescue (PCoAR) 717-589-3005 Millerstown, PA www.perrycountyanimalrescue.org

Hubert met Ned, the rescue dog tester and he has decided Hubert is not good with cats. We agree. No cats for Hubert.

animal.description:
Click my picture for more info. on me!
Meet Dia!

Dia is new to FHS, so we are only starting to get to know her. She is a one year old hound mix- probably with some Walker Coonhound in there. She is a lovely, sweet girl who likes to show off her sassy smarts. Like how she can get out of the fence, only to sit on the other side of it as a taunt.

She is a lovable girl who enjoys cuddling up with her family. Dia is good with other dogs and came to us from a large household. She is also good with kids, but she can be very bouncy and can easily knock small children over. She is a little unsure of leaving her home, so she is quiet with us for now and is only starting to come out of her shell. We will add more as we get to know her.

If you are interested in her, fill out an application at
www.fayettehumane.org/adopt/dogapplication

Due to COVID-19, we are not able to facilitate meet and greets until a family is approved and then only at the foster family's discretion. At this time, we are not holding dog adoptions at Petsmart.

**Applications can take anywhere from 5-7 business days to complete. When filling out an application, please scroll down after submitting it to be sure that the website accepted it and check for a confirmation email to be sure that your application went through. We respond by email, so please check your spam and trash folders.**

We are located in Fayette County, GA and are a foster based rescue without a shelter building.

Estimated DOB: 12/19/2019
Adoption fee: $250

CLICK HERE to APPLY TO ADOPT
or paste the following link in your browser: https://fayettehumane.org/adopt/dogapplication

All our dogs are tested for heartworms, spayed/neutered, up-to-date on age appropriate vaccines and flea prevention.

Cats are tested for FLV/FIV when age appropriate, as kittens tested at an age less than 16 weeks tends to lead to unreliable results. All our cats are spayed/neutered, up-to-date on age appropriate vaccines and flea prevention.

animal.description:
Meet Buddy in Colorado!!!

Buddy has the perfect name because he wants to be everybody’s best friend. He is super friendly and sweet, and loves getting cuddles and lying across your lap or leaning into you. He’ll make you feel like a million bucks!!!!

Buddy is 10 yrs old and weighs in around 100 pounds. We think he is a mastiff mix, and he has the most gentle and loving personality. 

Buddy would love a home where his humans are around a lot, and where he can get tons of attention. He gets along well with other dogs and cats, and has a great mix of energy and mellowness. 

Buddy has a tendency to have allergies and itchy skin, so he needs a good quality limited ingredient food. He is also currently on an allergy medication that seems to be helping too.

We are partnering with Golden Growls Senior Rescue to find this gentle giant a loving forever home. Please help us spread for Buddy, and if you are interested in him please fill out our adoption survey: https://www.olddogsnewdigs.com/adoption-survey/. Thanks!!!

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior pets have a history of being kept up to date on vaccines, annual exams and recommended bloodwork. We also do home checks to make sure that your home environment meets the needs of the particular dog you are interested in.

If you’re interested in adoption, please fill out our online adoption survey at https://www.olddogsnewdigs.com/adoption-survey/

animal.description:
*** Avail Wednesday 1/27 *** Siena is a young hound mix. She is a very friendly dog and greets everyone she meets with a wagging tail. She seems especially fond of children, and always gives them her "full body wag". She loved getting pets from all the neighborhood children! Siena is housebroken and sleeps quietly in her crate all night with no accidents. She made great progress with leash walking using an EZ Walk Harness. She often gets excited when she sees other dogs while on a walk, but is easily distracted with high-value treats (she's very fond of hot dogs!). Siena will sit on command. Siena played very nicely with the resident dog who was of similar size. She enjoyed running and playing in the fenced backyard. Siena would sometimes fetch a ball (if there was a treat involved) but she would also be just as happy to play with a ball by herself, tossing the ball in the air and then chasing it. Siena loves stuffed toys, especially ones that squeak. She thoroughly enjoys chewing on a Benebone, but didn't show much interest in a frozen peanut butter Kong. Siena is a sweet, friendly dog who has a lot of love to share with her lucky forever family! Make an appointment to come and meet her today!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
NAME - Ziva. 
BREED - Hound mix. 
AGE - 8 years. 

Ziva is hitting her golden years, but age hasn't hit her yet! She has tons of pep in her step, and loves adventures outside. This bouncy girl will take attention, but is also cool and independent, enjoying her "me time". Ideally, she'll find a quiet home to live out the rest of her days comfortably, with an equally cool human to bunk with. She loves hanging out in the fresh air and bird watching, so if you're looking for a porch buddy, Ziva is your girl. 

OKAY WITH DOGS? Can play well with certain dogs outside - can NOT live with another dog. 
OKAY WITH CATS? No. 
GOOD WITH KIDS? No. 

- To learn if this pet is still available for adoption, please check their adoption profile on our Adopets site, by visiting www.ucspca.org. -

animal.description:
Misty von Milow is a stunning 1-2 year old German Shepherd. This mid-energy, sweet girl is still trying to figure out her situation. She seems lovely, she just needs some reassurance and time to adjust. She is getting used to the rescue and becoming more sure of herself day by day. On the leash, she can be a bit shy but ultimately walks well and can walk in a pack of other dogs. Misty enjoys being by her human’s side, whether that’s out on walks, getting pets or head scratches back at the rescue or out in the yard during playtime with other pups. She prefers calm dogs like herself but generally sticks to herself or her humans. She is a pleasure to be around and it’s even more rewarding to see her become more and more comfortable every day. Will you be the one to help her continue her life journey?
